<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-14 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE President Warns Against Threat Caused By </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 14 (Xinhua) -- United Arab Emirates' (UAE)
President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan warned today that the
continuation of Iraqi people's suffering caused by the
U.N. sanctions would threat the Gulf region's "future and fate."
</P>
<P>
In his annual address at the meeting of the UAE's Federal
National Council held here today, Zayed said Iraq has suffered
heavy losses in the past years and such losses would push the Gulf
region to a razor's edge.
</P>
<P>
"The continuation and aggravation of the Arab Iraqi people's
sufferings will impose deep and dangerous effects on the future
and fate of the (Gulf) region," he warned.
</P>
<P>
"We do hope the international community to put an immediate
end to the Iraqi people's sufferings...to keep the region
away from violence and wars," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, which has been under the U.N. sanctions since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait, recently claimed that it has lost 1.25 million
women and children during the past seven years due to the lack of
food and medicines.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. report showed that Iraq also suffered heavy income
losses which were estimated at 120 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gulf Arab states, including the UAE, have repeatedly called
for the end of the U.N. sanctions against Baghdad to ease the
sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Some Gulf officials privately voiced their worries that the
stern U.N. sanctions could force Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
to stake everything on a single throw against the Gulf region's
security if Baghdad was continuously kept difficult to "breathe."
</P>
<P>
In his address, the UAE president also stressed that the UAE
"strongly and completedly" supports Iraq's territorial integrity,
independence and sovereignty, and refuses any foreign interference
in Iraq's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He did not identify the foreign interference, but observers
here noted that he could implicate Turkey's military incursions
into northern Iraq and Iran's air raids against rebel bases in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops have repeatedly crossed the border with Iraq to
search anti-government Kurdish guerrillas in the mountainous
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iran, a long-term potential threat considered by Gulf Arab
countries, recently launched air strikes against rebels based in
southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and other Gulf Arab states strongly blasted the
military operations and called for fully maintaining the
territorial integrity of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
