<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poaching Increase in Southern Africa Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Conservationists in southern
Africa today deny there has been an increase in poaching in the
region since the convention on international trade in endangered
species (CITES) decided to downlist the African elephant in June.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted statements issued today by the
Zimbabwe Trust and the Wildlife Environment Society of South
Africa as saying that there had not been any measurable increase
in elephant poaching so far while in some areas it had gone down.
</P>
<P>
At the June conference of parties to CITES in Harare, the
African elephant was downlisted from appendix one where trade is
banned to appendix two where controlled trade is allowed.
</P>
<P>
Conditions were set under which Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe
could resume controlled but strictly limited trade in ivory by
1999 provided there was no increase in poaching activities.
</P>
<P>
Many animal rights groups, which heavily fought the
downlisting, have published materials claiming that there was an
increase in poaching activities in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
But Secretary General of the Zimbabwe Trust Rob Monro said
Traffic, the official monitor for decisions made by CITES had not
found any evidence of the purported increase in poaching.
</P>
<P>
''As far as we can see in some places, the rate of poaching
actually fell over the past six months. If poaching is going to
escalate now, we will be inclined to blame those who claim now
that it is on the increase,'' Monro said.
</P>
<P>
The U.K.-based International Fund for Animal Welfare (IFAW)
reported recently that a total of 29 elephants had been poached
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Wildlife Society has refuted this saying poaching
had actually gone down compared to the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
Board member of Wildlife and Environment Society of South
Africa Bruce Davidson said the reports of increased poaching were
surprising as it appeared that poaching levels may even be lower
since the CITES decision was made.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has already voted to follow the CITES
decision by incorporating the regislations set on trade in
elephant products in the European law.
</P>
<P>
It will therefore be possible for commercial shipments of
elephant hides and personal tourist items of leather and ivory to
be made from Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe to enter Europe
beginning the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
