<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Find Planets around Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- British scientists using a new
astronomical camera have found what they believe is conclusive
evidence of planets circling four of the closest stars to Earth,
The Observer newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"It's planets. I've no doubt," Wayne Holland, one of a team of
scientists at Edinburgh's Royal Observatory who developed the
camera, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new camera, the Sub-millimeter Common User Bolometer Array
(SCUBA), is cooled to within one-tenth of a degree of absolute
zero, minus 273 Centigrade, enabling it to pick up faint heat
emanations from gas and dust particles warmed by stellar
radiation.
</P>
<P>
It has been fitted to the Observatory's Maxwell telescope 4,000
meters above sea level on the Mauna Kea mountain in Hawaii and
used to probe four stars, Beta Pictoris, Fomalhaut, Epsilon
Eridani and Vega.
</P>
<P>
These stars are all relatively young -- about 200 million years
old compared with several billion for our Sun -- and are all
within 24 light years from Earth.
</P>
<P>
The Observer said the scientists reported to Britain's Royal
Astronomical Society at a meeting last week that each star was
surrounded by a vast halo of dust, but the center of the area was
clear of material.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the leader of the survey team, Professor Ben
Zuckerman of the University of California, as saying there were a
number of possible explanations -- but planets were far the most
likely.
</P>
<P>
Zuckerman said: "Radiation from the stars may have driven these
particles deeper into space. However, easily the most convincing
reason is that they have been swept clean by planets orbiting near
each star."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the discovery was bound to lead to
speculation that planets were a common feature of our galaxy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Ruling Party to Win Local Elections: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Liberation Front of
Mozambique would win in the local elections if held in Maputo and
Matola now, the Mozambique Information Agency reported today
quoting a survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted recently by the Sampling Office under
the Comprehensive Polytechnic University of Mozambique shows that
1,325 people of 2,560 interviewed would vote for the ruling
Liberation Front in local elections to be held on May 29 next
year.
</P>
<P>
It means that the ruling party will win more than half of
votes in the forthcoming local elections, the report said, adding
that only 14.8 percent of the surveyed, that is 380 people, would
vote for the biggest opposition party the National Resistance
Movement of Mozambique (Renamo).
</P>
<P>
According to the survey by the private university, among the
surveyed, 53.5 percent said that they voted for the Liberation
Front of Mozambique in 1994 general elections and 10.4 percent
said they voted for the Renamo.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that the support rate for the ruling
party has dropped a little bit while that for the Renamo has
picked up in Maputo and Matola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
