<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Political Unification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The African National
Congress (ANC) would welcome a merger with the Inkatha Freedom
Party (IFP) in the interests of national unity, South African
President Nelson Mandela said here today.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed in his capacity as outgoing ANC president ahead of
next week's party national conference, Mandela said a merger
between the two parties would be "a very progressive development"
as South Africans needed to speak with one voice.
</P>
<P>
Representing eight million people of the Zulu tribe, the IFP
is the largest black opposition in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the proposed merger had nothing to do with black
unity, as the country had had progressed beyond ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
"It is not question of black unity, but the unity of the
entire country that will be the guiding principle. We are busy
with the task of uniting the entire nation. That's why we have
the government of national unity," said the president.
</P>
<P>
Mandela dismissed the perception that this would lead to a
single party state as in some other parts of the continent, or
that it would polarize South Africa on racial lines.
</P>
<P>
The ANC was not only looking to the IFP, but wanted a
relationship with other political parties as well, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
