<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-14 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Chief Says Progress Being Made in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief inspector Richard
Butler said today "some progress has been made" in today's
technical talks between U.N. arms inspectors and Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
Butler, Chairman of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating weapons of mass destruction in
Iraq, made the remarks at a press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that he and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz will
attend this evening's technical talks between both sides.
</P>
<P>
Aziz requested him on telephone that both of them take part in
tonight's technical talks, said Butler, describing Aziz's offer
as "positive development."
</P>
<P>
"He (Aziz) would be in a position to give me a fuller report on
the biological area tonight," said Bulter, adding that he
anxiously expects the report.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the UNSCOM today started the technical talks on
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction. But Butler and
Aziz did not attend the talks during the day.
</P>
<P>
Bulter is scheduled to discuss with Aziz on Monday the issue of
arms inspectors' access to Iraq's sensitive sites, including
presidential palaces, which Iraq has declared off-limits for
concerns of national security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the Iraqi News Agency, U.N. inspection
teams continued their mission today with 11 teams searching 19
sites with full cooperation of the Iraqi side.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. arms inspectors are authorized to verify that Iraq has
complied with the U.N. orders issued in 1991 after the Gulf War to
destroy long-range missiles and biological, chemical and nuclear
weapons. Until then will the U.N. Security Council lift the
economic sanctions on Iraq imposed in 1990 after its invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
