<HEADLINE> Nigeria Moving to Restructure Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is in
motion to make its foreign policy more pro-active rather than
reactive to enable the country to stand the challenges of the
next century.
</P>
<P>
In his state of the world address in the capital Abuja
Saturday, Head of State General Sani Abacha said, "a
comprehensive process of revamping and restructuring its foreign
policy apparatus" was underway to make it more result oriented.
</P>
<P>
He said the overriding aim of the nation's foreign policy was
the constant protection and safeguarding of national interest,
the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the main thrust of the policy was the
struggle for self determination, the alleviation of poverty and
the pursuit of self-reliant development.
</P>
<P>
Abacha noted that following development in science and
technology in the past two and half decades, the world could be
described as a global village.
</P>
<P>
But he lamented that underdeveloped nations had not benefited
much from the so called globalization.
</P>
<P>
"In reality, we have not seen a global village of
interdependence, but a global village of grossly unequal
partners," Abacha said.
</P>
<P>
The globalization had not succeeded in reducing the historical
contradictions between the developed and developing countries, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Abacha reiterated that Nigeria would continue to pursue the
goals of the Economic Community of West African States and the
economic community of African states as outlined by the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
He also touched the sanctions imposed by the Commonwealth on
Nigeria, saying that the measures were not only undeserved, but
also unfair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
