<HEADLINE> President: Iran Expects Dialogue with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami said here today that he expected a dialogue between Iran
and the United States, hinting at a possible rapprochement between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"I want to have a philosophical and historical interchange
with the American people and believe that whatever the
intellectual interchanges go ahead, the world will achieve
peace," Khatami said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that he respects the U.S. administration because "the
U.S. government is elected by the American people."
</P>
<P>
However, Khatami blamed U.S. statesmen for having fallen
behind the times, saying that the world has changed but the
U.S. policies remained the same as before.
</P>
<P>
U.S. statesmen should understand their times and the realties
facing the world better, he said, adding that the world is moving
toward a multi-polar system, but the U.S. is trying to impose its
objectives on other nations and push the world toward a unipolar
system.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Iran broke their diplomatic relations
following the 1979 storming of Iranian students at the American
embassy in Tehran and capturing its staff members as hostages
for more than one year.
</P>
<P>
Washington started a strict economic sanction on Tehran since
June, 1995 and threatened to punish foreign companies which have
an investment of over 20 million U.S. dollars in Iran's oil and
gas industries.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides have taken some steps toward the
rapprochement after Khatami won a landslide victory in the May
presidential elections and announced moderate foreign policies of
developing friendly relations and cooperation with the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
Khatami rejected the claim that Iran was isolated in the
world, saying that Tehran played an important role in the
world's affairs, particularly in the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the best time for improving relations between
Iran and the regional states has been provided, saying that
"there may be political differences between Iran and other
Islamic and Arab states, but, there exist numerous common
grounds, so we hope that dialog would serve to resolve our
differences while honoring our principles." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
