<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for More US Pressure on Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan
today called on the United States to exert more pressure on Israel
to make it abide by all the signed agreements in a bid to put the
Middle East peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
Hassan made the remark while meeting U.S. Assistant Secretary
of State Martin Indyk, who arrived here today as part of his
regional tour aimed at paving the way for the upcoming talks
between U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Israeli and
Palestinian leaders, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.S. to put more pressure on Israel in order to
make the Jewish state implement its commitments with regards to
troop redeployment in the West Bank, the Gaza airport and other
outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. should play a more active role in the peace process,
Petra quoted the crown prince as saying.
</P>
<P>
On the U.S. side, Indyk briefed Hassan on the outcome of his
tour to the region and stressed the U.S.' commitment to push the
peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. appreciated the role played by Jordan in helping
achieve a comprehensive and permanent peace that respects the
rights of all the parties, said Indyk who met Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Indyk said that in Albright's upcoming meetings with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Arafat, she was expected
to press Netanyahu to present a full plan for the troop
withdrawals in order to allow the two sides to enter long-delayed
negotiations for a final peace treaty and break the nine-month
deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In late November, Netanyahu's ministers agreed in principle
to conduct a troop withdrawal from the West Bank, but since then
they have been unable to agree on the share of land to be handed
over to the Palestinians. Hardliners in the Israeli government
opposed to a larger handover.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, however, refused Israel's redeployment plan
to withdraw troops from 6 to 8 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The already signed Palestinian-Israeli interim accords
stipulate that Israeli redeployment from 90 percent of the West
Bank should be implemented in a three-phase withdrawal to be
finished by mid-1998. 
</P>
