<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Kills Over 60 in Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar today began to
take precautionary measures to check further spread of cholera
over 500 confirmed patients have been hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said that 37 were killed between
Saturday and Sunday while 210 confirmed patients were admitted on
Saturday alone to the Mnazi Mmoja General Hospital, the largest
medical institution in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Although Zanzibar's Minister for Health, Saidi Bakari Jecha,
did not give the age nor gender proportion of the confirmed
cholera deaths and admitted patients, reliable sources said today
that children were the worst affected.
</P>
<P>
Following an emergency meeting of the National Cholera Control
Committee, the government immediately took measures to check the
epidemic which is wreaking havoc for the second time on the Isles
this year.
</P>
<P>
Measures announced include the ban on all festive public
gatherings and sales of all liquid food items, such as juices and
ice creams. Hotel owners and residents have been urged to
maintain high standards of hygiene and proper sanitation to
contain the disease.
</P>
<P>
The government continued to broadcast messages, urging the
public to observe hygiene including boiling all drinking water
and using chlorinated water.
</P>
<P>
Police and security guards have to work overtime to control a
huge crowd of relatives and friends who had gathered at the Mnazi
Mmoja Hospital to know the fate of their hospitalized kith and
kin.
</P>
<P>
Security has also been stepped up to check movement of
visitors at the hospital. Many residents were seen at various
pharmacies in a frantic effort to obtain supplies of antibiotics
such as tetracycline for prevention purposes.
</P>
<P>
Most parents have confined their children indoors as a
precautionary measure against the epidemic, most prevalent during
rainy seasons.
</P>
<P>
Jecha warned that those who plan to prepare feasts and
gatherings which are among chief sources of cholera will face
prosecution in accordance with cholera quarantine regulations.
</P>
<P>
He said the programs are underway to initiate several other
emergency clinics in the areas where the disease is rampant so as
to minimize the congestion in Mnazi Mmoja Hospital and enable
health personnel to deal with the problem at once in nearby
clinics.
</P>
<P>
The health minister appealed to anyone who may develop even
the mildest symptoms of cholera to report to the hospital for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
When death occurs at home, it should also be reported to
obtain expertise consultation and for burial arrangements. Six
patients have been reported to have died at home since the
disease outbroke, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
