<HEADLINE> Nigerian Experts Worried at Cancer Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian medical experts have
given a grim assessment of the threat of cancer, saying that more
people in the country will be killed by the disease in the years
to come.
</P>
<P>
"We expect deaths from cancer to rise by 77 percent from now
till the year 2020," said Abayomi Ferreira, president of the
Guild of Medical Directors of Nigeria, quoted by the News Agency
of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on cancer here over the weekend, the president
noted that deaths from communicable, maternal and nutritional
deficiency diseases were expected to drop by more than half
within the same period.
</P>
<P>
Apart from spreading various means of treatment, he called on
the government to launch a public health education scheme.
</P>
<P>
In the case of patients with cancer of the breast, according
to him, even some high grade health workers, including nurses,
headed for prayer houses instead of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Thus public enlightenment on the disease was an urgent job, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Cancer was first diagnosed in Nigeria in 1934. 
</P>
</TEXT>
