<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Deliberates Further Pullback, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet today held
its first deliberation on the planned second redeployment in
the West Bank and guidelines on permanent talks with the
Palestinians, but failed to reach a solution.
</P>
<P>
During the seven-hour marathon session chaired by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the ministers reviewed two maps of
Israeli interests presented by Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
and National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Netanyahu said "the Israeli government
will make decisions not under pressure but with responsibility
to do what is right for the country."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks were apparently referring to media reports
that the United States is exerting pressure on Israel to make an
earlier decision on the further redeployment and final-status
talks so to advance the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
A government statement issued after the meeting said that the
cabinet would hold its second session Tuesday to further discuss
the issues in a bid to draw a final map of guidelines, which
Netanyahu is expected to present to U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright when they meet Thursday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for his meeting with Albright, Netanyahu is to
hold a meeting tonight with visiting U.S. Assistant Secretary of
State Martin Indyk who has already met with several Israeli
ministers and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Immigration and Absorption Minister Yuri Edelstein told Israel
Radio that it was still too early to talk about the results of
the first cabinet meeting. But he disclosed that the gap between
the two maps presented by Mordechai and Sharon is not too big
and the cabinet will reach a consensus soon.
</P>
<P>
In his map, Sharon proposes creating two security zones to
ensure Israel's security: one 20-kilometer zone east of the
Green Line to divide Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas,
and another seven to 10 kilometers zone along the Jordan
River. Sharon calls for retaining control over the water sources
and all Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's map, which was drawn up by the defense and
security establishment, has demarcated Israel's military red
lines and several options for the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to go ahead with the second
redeployment and permanent talks with the PNA has triggered
strong opposition from some hardline coalition members and the
rightwing settlers.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Zevulun Hammer and Transportation Minister
Yitzhak Levy of the rightist National Religious Party today
presented Netanyahu and the cabinet a draft resolution that
conditions any Israeli troop redeployment on the PNA's
fulfillment of its commitments, including extradition of
murderers and terrorists.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution also stated that, in the final
settlement, Israel should oppose the establishment of a
Palestinian state and return of Palestinian refugees, and must
strengthen its hold to the disputed Jerusalem and the existence
of all Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of settlers from settlements in the West
Bank demonstrated outside the Prime Minister's Office today to
protest the government plan to carry out the second redeployment
and the U.S. pressure on Israel to proceed ahead with the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators, including many children who blew noisy
whistles, held banners reading "Stop Oslo Process," "Americans
Don't Interfere," and "Time-out of Concessions." A number of
Jewish settlers in the West Bank also held a strike today to
protest the planned redeployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
