<HEADLINE> Taya Wins in Presidential Election in Mauritania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Mauritania's President
Maaouya Ould Sid'ahmed Taya has won more than 90 percent of the
vote in Friday's presidential election, a report reaching here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Official news media in the west African country said today
that Taya's vote was 90.14 percent, and the final result will
be announced later today.
</P>
<P>
An official of Taya's Democratic and Social Republican Party
(DSRP) said Taya had won 90.25 percent of the vote in Mauritania,
against less than seven percent for his closest rival, former
minister Mohamed Lemine Chbih Ould Cheikh Mailainine.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition parties boycotted the poll, saying it was
rigged in advance.
</P>
<P>
Attention therefore focused on the turnout, which the DSRP
official put at 72 percent and other sources said was at least 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Ould Daddah, leader of the Union of Democratic Forces
(UDF) and runner-up in the last presidential election in 1992,
cited many irregularities, claiming that some polling stations
had stayed open well after the scheduled 1900 gmt close on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Taya, a Moor, came to power in a bloodless coup in 1984 and
was elected in 1992 with over 62 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Light-skinned Moors, who freely owned black slaves until
slavery was abolished in 1980, have dominated Mauritanian
politics since independence from France in 1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
