<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-14 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Satisfied with EU Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides today expressed full satisfaction with a European Union
(EU) decision to start membership talks with Cyprus in March.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his return from Luxembourg, where
Clerides attended a meeting Saturday with the EU leaders,
European Commission members and leaders of the associated
countries, he said the decision made for EU enlargement at the
two-day Luxembourg summit was of "historical significance" for
both the EU and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important for the EU as it will enlarge the
group. At the same time, it is of paramount importance for
Cyprus as it opens the door for joining the EU.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said the EU decision would benefit the people of
Cyprus as a whole, especially the future generations in terms of
progress, welfare and security.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the decision had sent a message to Turkey
that to join the EU it should constructively contribute to finding
a Cyprus solution, within the U.N. framework and in accordance
with U.N. Security Council resolutions on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Replying to questions, the president said the Greek Cypriot
side would expect to see Turkey's reactions and act accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side was reported to be negative to the EU
decision, and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash was quoted as
saying Saturday that the EU decision was not helpful toward a
settlement to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Turkish Cypriot participation in an official
delegation of the Cyprus Republic for the EU accession
negotiations, Denktash said "if they (the EU) want our
participation, then they should recognize our state. There is no
other way."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared in 1983 a breakaway "the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which was only recognized
by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Turkish threat to annex the northern Cyprus if
the EU continues its plan to begin accession talks with the
Cypriot government, Clerides said that if Turkey went ahead to
gradually integrate the occupied northern part of the island,
"no country will accept this, neither Europe, nor the U.S., or
any other country."
</P>
<P>
He said that world leaders share the view that Cyprus'
accession course to the EU would be a catalyst for a solution to
the protracted Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
