<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-14 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticized for Execution of Jordanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Cairo-based Arab Human
Rights Organization today lashed out at Iraq for executing four
Jordanians for smuggling car parts, saying that such an act is a
violation of the principles of international justice.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency reported that in a statement
released here today, the group said the penalty should be
commensurate with the crime.
</P>
<P>
"The death penalty should be only limited to the most dangerous
crimes as stipulated in the international law on civil and
political rights, endorsed by Iraq," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The organization asked the Iraqi authorities to refrain from
issuing death sentences in such cases and to abide by
international human rights criteria especially as Iraq itself is
suffering from "justice imbalance" through the U.N.-imposed embargo
on the country for more than seven years.
</P>
<P>
The four Jordanians were executed Monday on charges of
smuggling car parts which are in short supply in Iraq due to the
U.N.-imposed sanctions for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Jordan Wednesday expelled seven Iraqi diplomats and recalled its
charge d'affaires back from Baghdad in retaliation for the
execution.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, however, defended its execution Thursday, saying that it
considered smuggling "a great danger to society." 
</P>
</TEXT>
