<HEADLINE> No Agreement in Sight Between Palestinians, Israel: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the United
States said here today no comprehensive agreement is in sight
between the Palestinians and Israel, whose final status talks is
still a vision.
</P>
<P>
Separate meetings due next week between U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will not lead to an
agreement, said U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk.
</P>
<P>
But the meetings will be a positive step to activate the peace
process between the Palestinians and Israel, Indyk said at a press
conference after meeting with Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel's proposed troop withdrawal in the West
Bank is far from enough.
</P>
<P>
Israel has proposed to pull back from 6-8 percent of the West
Bank, which the Palestinians have rejected.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official, who arrived here today as part of his
regional tour, appreciated Jordan's role in reviving the peace
process. 
</P>
