<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Penalize Belgium for Non-Respect of Wild Bird Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
announced that it had decided to seek a daily penalty of 7,750 ECU
(8,600 U.S. dollars) should Belgium not respect a European Court
of Justice ruling concerning wild bird conservation again.
</P>
<P>
The penalty was proposed in the commission's second application
to the court under the treaty of the European Union for Belgium's
failure to comply with a previous court judgement.
</P>
<P>
The case against Belgium related to non-respect of a 1987 court
judgement concerning failure to comply with a European Council
directive on the conservation of wild birds.
</P>
<P>
The council document created a conservation framework that
includes strict controls on hunting and other forms of
exploitation of wild birds.
</P>
<P>
The European Court of Justice denounced Belgium for its
permitting derogations from the directive's protection regime in
wider circumstances than the document allowed.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty, the legislative principles of the
15-nation union, allows the union's executive body, the European
Commission, to ask the European Court of Justice to impose a
financial penalty on the member state concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
