<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD: Asia Economy Slows Down Overall in Second Half 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report said a strong fall of stock values was marked in
Thailand in the first half of 1997, and it extended to other
economies of the region during the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
While the prices of stocks dropped in nearly all the countries
of the region after the middle of the year, the values of stocks
in Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines dropped by 40 percent in
mid-November as compared with the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that even in China, the rapid rise of stock
values has been interrupted since the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the currencies of the economies most directly
touched by the crisis, such as Malaysia and the Philippines,
dropped in value by 20-25 percent by mid-November.
</P>
<P>
The currencies of Chinese Taiwan and Singapore also dropped to
a lesser extent, while the Hong Kong dollar, which is the last
money subjected to speculation, kept its parity with the
U.S. dollar at the cost of higher interest rates and a strong fall
of its stock values, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said domestic demand and fixed investment have
fallen greatly in Thailand, and to a lesser extent, in the
Philippines, Malaysia and Indonesia, because of the weakening of
their stock markets and real estate markets, as well as the
postponement of some big infrastructure projects by these
countries.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the depreciation of their currencies has not been
sufficient to make for the losses they suffered through exports,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Although the economic growth rates of these economies should
not be absent except in Thailand, the economic activities have
greatly slowed down as compared with the expansion rhythm of the
previous years.
</P>
<P>
The depreciations of the currencies are bringing about
inflation pressures, but the pressure will not be fully felt until
1998, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD: Asia Economy Slows Down Overall in Second Half 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report said that in economies less touched by the crisis,
such as China, Singapore, Chinese Taiwan and Hong Kong, economic
growth has remained vigorous up to now.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, the manufacturing sector has just experienced a
vivid expansion, because of accelerating increase of consumption
and exports. In Taiwan, the formation of capital has been
maintained, although private consumption has shown signs of
difficulty, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, investments have greatly increased in the real
estate sector and mechanical construction, while the spending on
consumption remains relatively stationary, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report warned that the rising interest rates and the
effects of the negative heritage coming down from the Southeast
Asian crisis could weigh on the economic activities of Hong Kong
in the months to come.
</P>
<P>
In China, the growth remains stable despite a slowdown, as
compared with the "excessively rapid rhythm" registered in the
previous years, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said that the "restrictive monetary policy" and "a rigorous
control of credit" exerted by the Chinese government have
contributed to controlling inflation at a low level since the
second half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The vigor of Chinese exports has also stimulated the growth in
1997, but the domestic economy has recently shown certain signs of
slowdown, with high interest rates and weak growth of real
salaries greatly restricting the domestic demand and thus the
"internal motor of real GDP growth" in China.
</P>
<P>
The report went on to point out that the lowering of interest
rates in October by the People's Bank of China was aimed at
stimulating the growth of domestic consumption, encouraging
investments and controlling the cost of service for the debt owed
by state enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Goads Domestic Tourism After Luxor Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian citizens are moving in
place of foreigners at various spots of tourist attraction to
help their government tide over a difficult time following the
November terrorist attack targeting tourism.
</P>
<P>
Damage brought on the lucrative tourism industry by the
November 17 mass killings in Luxor can be contained within few
months through giving much-needed vigor to the domestic tourism,
according to Egypt's tourism officials.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Minister Mamdouh el-Beltagui at an emergency meeting
last weekend warned against any attempt by tourist companies to
reduce the price and organize trips outside Egypt, saying that it
would deny the government a large quota of hard currency and would
be too difficult to reverse the trend when the crisis ends.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the minister suggested that these companies should
overcome the temporary crisis by selling travel packages in the
Arab market and activate internal trips for Egyptians.
</P>
<P>
A set of important decisions have been endorsed to stanch the
tragic fallout of the Luxor incident at the meeting that included
a number of ministers, senior officials and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
Among the decisions was the "100-Day Program" to activate
domestic tourism, under which banks, political parties,
professional unions and sporting clubs organize trips for their
members to places of interest and archaeological sites in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen at the meeting have donated more than half a
million Egyptian pounds (about 150,000 U.S. dollars) and made over
100 offers to finance organized domestic trips for school children.
</P>
<P>
EgyptAir, which lost 85,000 passengers in the days immediately
after the massacre and was expecting a loss of up to 600 million
pounds (176.47 million dollars) in the coming six months, has
streamlined some flight routes and offered a 50 percent cut in the
domestic air fares.
</P>
<P>
Middle-class Egyptian families and secondary school and
university students used to shun the main tourist sites in Upper
Egypt, Sinai Peninsula and the Red Sea due to high costs of
accommodation and transport.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Hussein Kamel Bahauddin ratified a plan on
Saturday to send 6,000 high school students on trips to Luxor,
Aswan and the Red Sea tourist spots during the mid-school year
break that begins in late January.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Egyptian Gazette today quoted an Education
Ministry source as saying that the minister has allocated 1.5
million pounds (441,176 dollars) to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
Fifty delegations, comprising students from all provinces, will
be included in the trips aimed at spreading awareness among
students on the importance of the tourism industry and learning
the country's historical places at first hand.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been scrambling to save its 3.6 billion tourism
industry after six Islamic militants shot dead 58 foreign tourists
and four Egyptians before an ancient temple in Egypt's largest
tourist city of Luxor.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of tourists have canceled their trips to Egypt while
many foreign governments and tourist operators warned their
nationals to stay clear of Egypt at present.
</P>
<P>
According to a report on the official response of various
countries to the Luxor massacre, the Arab countries, Russia and
Latin America are relatively positive about Egypt's stability and
security, while some others like Britain, Switzerland, Japan and
Scandinavian countries are still suspicious. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Taxi Drivers Encouraged to Use Cleaner Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will encourage all
taxi operators to switch to environment-friendly liquefied
petroleum gas (LPG) after a one-year trial run with 30 LPG taxis,
said an official here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a forum on air pollution, Secretary for Planning,
Environment and Lands Bowen Leung said his bureau will devise a
scheme on the basis of the operating cost data obtained from the
trial to encourage the entire fleet of 17,800 taxis to use LPG
expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
"In parallel with the trial, we are working out plans to
develop a refilling network to dovetail with the large scale
introduction of LPG vehicles," he added.
</P>
<P>
Thirty trial taxis started to drive on Hong Kong streets in
November. They provide operational data on fuel consumption and
repair and maintenance requirements.
</P>
<P>
"So far, I am pleased to note that users of the LPG taxis are
satisfied with the performance of these vehicles," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
"We aim to apply the LPG vehicle technology to taxis as a start
and then extend to other classes of diesel vehicles such as public
light buses and small school buses," Leung continued.
</P>
<P>
LPG vehicles have been in use in a number of countries such as
Japan, the Netherlands and Italy, for over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Leung told the forum that to address air pollution issues in
the Pearl River Delta Region, the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) has agreed with neighboring Guangdong province to
set up a study group to exchange information on air quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
