<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Makes Appeal Against Maier's Disqualification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Austria ski federation said
on Monday it has made an appeal against Hermann Maier's
disqulification.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian was deprived of the championship in Sunday's World
Cup giant slalom at Val d'Isere, France, for taking off a ski
before crossing a red line in the finishing area and displayed it.
</P>
<P>
The International Skiing Federation (FIA) set the line to avoid
skiers making too much of a show of the Sponsor's skis.
</P>
<P>
The FIS awarded the title laterly to defending world champion
Michael Von Gruenigen of Switzerland, who finished second behind
Maier.
</P>
<P>
Federation official Hans Pum filed an official protest, saying
Maier "did not violate the spirit of the law".
</P>
<P>
Pum claimed FIS has misfunctioned the rule, which says skiers
will be disqualified when they take off both skis, while Maier
"only took off one".
</P>
<P>
Despite the disqualification Maier is still in the lead of the
overall standings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
