<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Must Slow Down its High Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan must slow down its
high population growth to meet the challenges of the 21st century,
said Nafis Sadik, Executive Director of the United Nations Fund
for Population Activities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting attended by economists here today, Nafis
said Pakistan had been left lagging behind other countries in the
region mainly because of its rapid population growth rate which
now stands at about 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1947 when Pakistan gained independence, it was the 13th most
populous country in the world with a population of 32.5 million,
but in 1996 it became the seventh with a population of 140
million, she said.
</P>
<P>
"No conceivable development pan can sustain such a rate of
population growth," she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nafis said, the inequality between the sexes in the
country had held back its development from the outset.
</P>
<P>
"Girls are less welcome in our families than boys," she said.
"At every economic level in Pakistan, resources are not equitably
distributed between men and women, girls and boys."
</P>
<P>
In Pakistan, girls have much fewer chances of going to school
than boys, get married earlier than boys and start having children
while they are still in their teens, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the rates of social investment in Pakistan were
considerably low compared with international norms and other
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
While priority for large-scale investments in industry and
industrial infrastructure was the norm in most countries in the
world half a century ago, it is clearly recognized today that
investment in the human resources development is equally
important, Nafis stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition on Chinese Historical Relics Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition on Chinese
cultural relics, the largest of its kind ever held in Hong Kong,
was officially opened at the Hong Kong Museum of Art today.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition offers a golden opportunity for Hong Kong people
 to appreciate "the rarest and most valuable collections" of over
30 museums and cultural institutes in China, the Provisional Urban
 Council said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, entitled "National Treasures -- Gems of China's
 Cultural Relics", was opened by Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
 the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China, and will be
 open to the public from December 16 to March 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The 163 art pieces on display are in a wide range of media,
including ceramics, bronzes, jades, gold and silver wares, oracle
bone, ivory, fresco, lacquer, kesi tapestry and painting.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits, mostly class I national treasures of China,
include pieces familiar to the people of Hong Kong such as the
terra-cotta warriors from the tombs of the Qin Dynasty (221-207
B.C.) and the well-known jade burial suit of Lord Liu Sheng of the
 Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-A.D. 24).
</P>
<P>
Some of the gems have never been shown outside China's mainland
 before. Among them are the Tang Dynasty (618-907) Buddhist
treasures, gold and silverware and porcelain from the unique
collection of the Museum of Famen Temple in Shaanxi province.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of the exhibits also include a 2.62-meter-high Shang
 Dynasty (c. 16th-11th centuries B.C.) bronze standing figure
excavated in Sichuan province; a Western Zhou Dynasty (c. 11th
century-771 B.C.) bronze tripod weighing 226 kilograms; a set of
26 bronze bells of the Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 B.C.)
and a 15-meter-long hand scroll of painting depicting the southern
 voyage of the Kangxi Emperor of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, presented by the Hong Kong Provisional Urban
Council and the State Bureau of Cultural Relics of China, featured
 important archaeological finds from various regions of China
dating from the Neolithic Period to the Qing Dynasty (c. 140th
century B.C. to A.D. 1911).
</P>
<P>
The exhibits, each with detailed illustration, are divided into
 seven sections in chronological order.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Ronald Leung Ding-bong,
chairman of the Provisional Urban Council, said these precious
cultural relics fully reveal the styles and techniques of Chinese
craft in the past ages and give a full picture of the history of
art development in China.
</P>
<P>
"At this important moment when Hong Kong reunites with China
and strides forward towards a historical new era, the holding of
an exhibition on gems of cultural relics helps the Chinese living
in Hong Kong to realize their wish to trace roots," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
This exhibitions "does not only provide a valuable opportunity
for appreciating the cultural relics, but also promotes our
understanding of Chinese culture and enrich our knowledge of the
customs, culture and beliefs of different regions of China at
various times," Leung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Sets Up Working Group to Deal with Bird Flu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) set up an
inter-department working group today to coordinate efforts towards
the prevention and control of the spread of a mysterious "bird
flu" that has killed two people.
</P>
<P>
A SAR government spokesman said the group, which comprises
representatives from various government departments, will hold its
first meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The group will coordinate measures necessary for the prevention
and control of the "bird flu," or H5N1 virus, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Chickens have been identified as the most likely source of a
new strain of the flu.
</P>
<P>
The move came after three more people were suspected last week
to have been stricken with the H5NI virus, bringing the number of
confirmed or suspected cases to seven.
</P>
<P>
A 5-year-old child died in May in the first known case of a
human contracting the virus. A 54-year-old man died early this
month, and a 2-year-old boy recovered after hospitalization in
November.
</P>
<P>
Three more people remained hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
The government also announced today that authorities in the
neighboring Guangdong Province have agreed to step up the
monitoring of chicken diseases at farms there.
</P>
<P>
A statement said Guangdong also plans to restrict chicken
exports to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Experts say they are baffled by the virus, and the hospital
authority has issued guidelines to the public and hospitals to
treat the potentially deadly flu.
</P>
<P>
There has been no evidence of human-to-human transmission of
the virus, and no infected chickens have been found at the market,
according to a source from the local health department.
</P>
<P>
Three more experts from the Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta in the United States arrived in Hong Kong Thursday to help
in the investigation, the source said.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization has reportedly been asked to
alert vaccine production centers worldwide to follow developments
with a view to preparing the necessary vaccine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
