<HEADLINE> S. Korean Presidential Race Enters Final Sprint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Kim Dae-jung, Lee Hoi-chang and
Rhee In-je, three front-runners in the South Korean presidential
race, are canvassing major cities and provinces in last-minute
efforts to gain votes.
</P>
<P>
The Grand National Party's candidate, Lee Hoi-chang, Monday,
toured the capital areas with his campaign slogan, "stability or
chaos", stressing the end of the period of "Three Kims' Politics"
(Kim Young-sam, Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong-pil).
</P>
<P>
The fresh presidential election is scheduled to begin on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lee, whose rating has risen since he joined forces with Cho
Soon's Democratic Party last November, is expected to visit Pusan
on Tuesday, one of the most important campaigning areas for him.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung, the presidential contender of the National
Congress for New Politics, and his supporters are making campaign
trips in Chungchong, Taegu, Kyongsang and Pusan.
</P>
<P>
Kim, 72, pledged to double South Korea's per capita income to
20,000 U.S. dollars if elected president.
</P>
<P>
He also said Lee, once prime minister of Kim Young-sam's
administration, should be held responsible for the current
economic crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the last poll released on November 26, Kim won the first
round with about 35 percent of the votes, while Lee ran second
with a razor-thin margin. South Korean's new election law forbids
any fresh poll among voters in December.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said Kim, who is making his fourth bid for the
presidency, has got a stronger base since his party allied with
Kim Jong-pil and Park Tae-joon's United Liberal Democrats last
November. The alliance would play an important role in the
forthcoming election.
</P>
<P>
Rhee In-je, the candidate of the New Party by the People, is
working hard in Pusan and South Kyongsang with a campaign slogan,
"generational changes."
</P>
<P>
Rhee, 48, is the youngest of the three front-runners in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Having acted as a provincial governor and labor minister in Kim
Young-sam's government, Rhee promised to revive the ailing South
Korean economy.
</P>
<P>
"I will reignite the fire of miracle at a time when people say
the Han River miracle is over," he said, referring to the nation's
economic boom in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Rhee's poll rating surpassed Lee Hoi-chang in early November
when the latter suffered considerably from accusations that his
two sons had intentionally lost weight to escape military service.
</P>
<P>
However, Rhee's popularity began declining after he set up a
new party for his presidential race. It was described as Kim
Young-sam's shadow as its major leaders are former aides of the
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
