<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD: Asian Economy Slows Down Overall in Second Half of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) says in an economic perspective
report published today that the dynamic economies of Asia, except
China's, manifested the signs of slow-down in the second half of
1997.
</P>
<P>
The economies, which include Hong Kong of China, China,
Malaysia, Singapore, Chinese Taiwan, the Philippines and Thailand,
experienced a ``relatively stable'' growth in the first half of
1997, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis originating this summer in Thailand had
exerted serious consequences on certain countries of the region,
notably Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
China has been greatly saved from the crisis so far with an
economic growth rate expected to be maintained at nine percent
annually as inflation remains low, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that the big deficits, strong dependence
on short-term foreign investments and rapid increases of
unproductive economic sectors in those crisis-affected economies
had resulted in the drop of confidence by international creditors.
</P>
<P>
These factors also make these economies vulnerable to the
withdrawal of foreign capital, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
