<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Plunges to New Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine currency, the
peso, plunged by 3.7 percent today to a new record low of 38.853
pesos against the U.S. dollar, closing at a weighted average of
38.359 pesos.
</P>
<P>
This is the third new historical low the peso has reached in
three straight trading days. Last Friday, it sank to a new low of
37.36 pesos a dollar from the previous day's 36.585 pesos.
</P>
<P>
So far the peso has devaluated by 47 percent since the
financial meltdown began to spill over from Thailand to other
Southeast Asian nations in July.
</P>
<P>
The Thai baht's fall to a new record today, heavy corporate
demand for the greenback and continuing regional currency worries
drove the peso down, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Bankers Association of the Philippines President Deogracias
Vistan said over radio that there is "pressure for the peso to
fall to 39 pesos" against the dollar due to regional developments.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
