<HEADLINE> Kinkel Regrets Turkey's Reaction to EU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel Monday regretted Turkey's announcement that it would end
political dialogue with the European Union (EU) because it had
been excluded from the EU expansion move in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Calling Turkey's reaction "harsh and brusque", Kinkel said: "It
should not and will not be Ankara's last answer."
</P>
<P>
The 15-member EU agreed at its Luxembourg summit last weekend
to invite Estonia, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland and
Slovenia as well as Cyprus to begin membership negotiations early
next year.
</P>
<P>
Five other eastern European candidates -- Bulgaria, Latvia,
Lithuania, Romania and Slovakia -- were placed on a slower
negotiating track.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU leaders did not accept Turkey, which has been
seeking EU membership for 34 years, as an official candidate.
Instead, they offered to invite Ankara to take part in a
pan-European conference next year as a means of keeping the
country within its enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government said the offer was insufficient and
declared that political dialogue with the EU was at an end.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters today in Bonn, Kinkel said that the
Luxembourg summit had made a fair proposal and expressed the hope
that "a more sober and detached point of view would prevail in
Ankara after the settling down of the last dust".
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Turkey's entry into the EU would have to go
through the human rights issues, its relations with Greece and the
Kurdish problem.
</P>
<P>
"But the door remains open," Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the notion that religious issues had influenced
the EU's consideration of Turkey's membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
