<HEADLINE> Fujian Province's First Expressway Begins Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The first expressway in east
China's Fujian province officially began operations today. The
expressway, 81.4 kilometers long, connects the cities of Quanzhou
and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
The Xiamen section of the Xiamen-Zhangzhou Expressway also
began trial running today.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Xiamen, Quanzhou and Zhangzhou are playing the
most active role in the province's economic activities, according
to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The opening of these freeways is expected to ease the area's
traffic and will help develop the local economy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Quanzhou-Xiamen Expressway cost 2.78 billion yuan,
including 127 million U.S. dollars in World Bank loans. The idea
to build the road was proposed in 1982, but the project was not
launched until 1994.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's expressways will be extended to 430 kilometers by the
end of this century to link Fuzhou, Putian, Quanzhou, Xiamen and
Zhangzhou, the five largest industrial cities in the province.
</P>
<P>
By then, the province's freeways are expected to connect with
Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces to the north and Guangdong Province
to the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
