<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Investment Helps China's Aid-The-Poor Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- As many as eight million
poverty-stricken people in west and southwest parts of China have
benefited from World Bank loans of 610 million U.S. dollars for
aid-the-poor projects.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995 China has cooperated with the World Bank on
aid-the-poor projects in the country's western and southwestern
areas including Guangxi Zhuang, Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia
autonomous regions; and Guizhou, Yunnan, Sichuan, Shaanxi, Gansu
and Qinghai provinces.
</P>
<P>
Since the country opened up in late 1978, China's economy has
grown rapidly. While the country still has more than 58 million
people living in poverty, most of those inhabit the arid and
mountainous areas in west China.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's participation in the projects is viewed as an
important force for helping the country eliminate poverty by the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The aid-the-poor projects cover a wide range of fields such as
land development, rural infrastructure, enterprise development,
education, health care and the establishment of organizations.
</P>
<P>
The "Southwest Project" is the country's first aid-the-poor
effort which introduced World Bank loans. The project was begun in
1995 and covers the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, and Guizhou
and Yunnan provinces. The project is the largest of its kind in
the country in the use of overseas investment and has so far cost
a total of more than 1.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Three years of effort has helped Guangxi, Guizhou and Yunnan
add more than 700-kilometers of rural roads and 3,570-hectares of
terraced fields, and transform 12,000-hectares of middle- and
low-yield farmlands. More than 370,000 local poor now have access
to water supply and a number of facilities have been built for the
development of local education, health care and industries.
</P>
<P>
Another project covering Sichuan and Shaanxi provinces and
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region is well under way. It is estimated
to cost more than 3.3 billion yuan, including 200 million U.S.
dollars in World Bank loans. The project is expected to help more
than 2.3 million poverty-stricken people get enough food and
clothing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Leads Trend in Life Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- In Shanghai, 15 percent of
local residents have bought life insurance policies -- 6 percent
more than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yongyuan, a local insurance expert, attributed the fast
development of the industry in the city to its booming economy.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is 15-to-18 years ahead of the country's average in
terms of its economic development, which has led to a remarkable
increase in local income, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shanghai has entered into the period of an aging
population and negative population growth, far ahead of the
country's average.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the ratio was 6-4 between property insurance and life
insurance, but the ratio reversed in 1996, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 11 Chinese and foreign insurance companies are doing
business in Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
