<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand, Hong Kong Take Titles in World Windsurfing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's Aaron McIntosh
took the men's title and Lee Lai-shan of China's Hong Kong won the
women's crown at the Mistral Olympic class world windsurfing
championships off Fremantle, Western Australia, Monday.
</P>
<P>
McIntosh won the victory after starting the final day in second
place, behind Amit Inbar of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Inbar wrecked his chances by finishing 34th in the opening race
of the day, in which McIntosh was third.
</P>
<P>
Inbar hung on to be second overall, while Portugal's Joao
Rodrigues captured third position.
</P>
<P>
Rodrigues, ranked number one in the world, finished equal on
points with New Zealander John-Paul Tobin, but was awarded the
bronze medal on a countback.
</P>
<P>
In an intense battle in the women's division, Lee closed a
13-point gap on the morning leader, Alessandra Sensini, of Italy,
to jump from third to snatch the gold in the last race of the day.
</P>
<P>
Sensini was second and New Zealand's Olympic silver medallist
Barbara Kendall won the bronze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
