<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Unemployment Rate Rises to 2.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's
seasonally-adjusted unemployment rate was marginally higher at 2.4
percent in the September-November period, according to the latest
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figure rose slightly from the August-October period when
the rate stood at 2.3 percent, the Census and Statistics
Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region's (SAR)
government said today.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the SAR government said overall labor market
conditions tended to ease in recent months, but new jobs continued
to be generated, with total employment showing solid growth.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that the underemployment rate was
marginally higher at 1.1 percent in the three months to November
as compared with the 1 percent in the three months to October.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the increase in the jobless rate in the
three months to November mainly occurred in the retail and
transport sectors and restaurants and hotels, noting that the
situation in other major sectors was broadly stable.
</P>
<P>
In the three months ending October this year, total employment
in the SAR grew by 4.9 percent over a year earlier, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
