<HEADLINE> Informal Summit of East Asia Held in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of ASEAN and
China, Japan and South Korea held their first informal summit here
today with a shared view on the perspective, development and
cooperation of East Asia in the 21 century.
</P>
<P>
As the summit was informal, the leaders were free to deliver
speeches in a happy and relaxed manner.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his speech entitled "Join Hands in Cooperation and
Build a Future Together," Chinese President Jiang Zemin recalled
the profound changes and tremendous progress that have taken place
in East Asia in the 20th century, especially in the past two or
three decades. Relatively sound conditions are available for East
Asia to raise its economic and social development to a new level
in the 21st century, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also stressed the need to look squarely into the
difficulties and obstacles on the way ahead such as irrational
economic structure, imperfect financial system, extensive mode of
growth and backward infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He said Southeast Asia's financial turmoil in recent months has
taught people a profound lesson and stressed that East Asian
countries should further strengthen cooperation for the benefit of
the peoples in the region.
</P>
<P>
Attending the summit were Chinese President Jiang, Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and South Korean Prime Minister
Koh Kun, host Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad,
Philippine President Fidel Ramos, Chairman of the Myanmar State
Peace and Development Council Than Shwe, Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai, Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, Brunei Sultan
Hassanal Bolkiah, Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai, Lao
Prime Minister Khamtay Siphandone and Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas who represented President Soeharto.  
</P>
