<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Firms Reduce Losses, Increase Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The government's efforts to
help state-owned industrial enterprises reduce their losses and
increase profits have yielded notable results in the first three
quarters of this year.
</P>
<P>
The good news was attributed to constant improvement in the
country's macro-economic environment and the implementation of
concerned policies and measures.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made jointly by the State Statistical
Bureau, the Ministry of Finance and the State Economic and Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, local governments at all levels
have increased efforts to reform enterprises and to supervise
major debt-ridden firms. The general performance of state
companies had improved, but quite a number remain in the red.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, 674,000 state-owned industrial firms
produced 199.66 billion yuan in pre-tax profits and 22.56 billion
yuan in net profits, up 10.31 percent and 67.74 percent over the
corresponding period last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The composite index of the economic performance of state
industrial firms went up 2.59 percent compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Companies owned by the central government performed better than
those owned by local governments in the period as the former have
reduced their losses and increased profits.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, centrally owned firms made a net
profit of 30.99 billion yuan, up 43.3 percent year-on-year, while
locally owned companies suffered a net loss of 252 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, state-owned industrial enterprises in 14
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities were in the
black, one more than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Major profitable state companies have played a big role in
reducing losses, while a large number of small- and medium-size
state firms are suffering losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
