<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits New High in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Following weaker-than-expected
business confidence shown in a quarterly survey of the Bank of
Japan (BOJ), the U.S. dollar hit a high of 131.60 yen in Tokyo on
Monday, the highest in five years and seven months.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the dollar was quoted at 131.35-37 yen, up from
130.80-82 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, and from 130.25-35 yen late
Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
The BOJ said the Tankan index, measuring the sentiment of
corporate managers of big manufacturers, declined from positive
three in September to minus 11 in December. The central bank also
said the leading non-manufacturers' index also fell from minus 15
in September to minus 20 in December.
</P>
<P>
The lackluster report sent the dollar above the mid-131 yen
level after sinking to a low of 130.25 yen earlier in the day,
dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
