<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Readiness to Improve Ties with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran today restated that it
was interested in improving relations with the European countries
following the resolution of the diplomatic row with the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"We are interested in improving economic relations with the
European countries based on respect for mutual principles and
values," Iran News today quoted deputy foreign minister for
economic affairs Mahmoud Vaezi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vaezi said that the Iranian government would discuss the
conditions for relations between Iran and the European countries
following the return of the EU ambassadors to Iran and their
Iranian counterparts to Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the relations between Iran and
Germany in the future needs to be reconsidered and reconstructed
"since the recent political problems with Germany was followed
by certain reflections in other European countries."
</P>
<P>
"Obviously a prolonged and stable economic relationship
necessitates a trustworthy political relationship," Vaezi said,
adding that political relationship could not be differentiated
from that of the economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the EU countries cooled down with
the withdrawal of EU ambassadors from Tehran after the Berlin
court issued statement accusing Iranian leaders of sponsoring
terrorist activities in Germany against Iranian outlawed Kurdish
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic standstill was over last month only after
the two sides compromised on the return of the EU ambassadors
in two groups, with the German envoy as the last one to be
back in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Vaezi said that Iran and the European countries have always
been good partners and have cooperated in energy, mining,
industrial and agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
"Trusting the existing relationship they could move on under
new circumstances," the Iranian official said, naturally with
the ambassadors' return "we will be looking forward to observe
relations in a better political climate."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Iran's policy was to focus on the export
of petrochemical byproducts as a possible replacement for crude
oil, saying that "our tenders are placed for the participation
of all countries and are not allotted to certain companies."
</P>
<P>
Vaezi also reiterated Iran's desire to establish an Islamic
common market despite the difficulties facing the Islamic
world.
</P>
<P>
The eighth summit of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) approved the Iranian proposal on an Islamic
common market and assigned a special committee to follow up
the issue and report to the next foreign ministers' meeting to
be held in Doha 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
