<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Network Useful in Chinese Army to Treat Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Computer has become an
important means to treat the ill or save the life of the wounded
in the Chinese army, military sources said.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 military hospitals have been linked to a computer
network which helps doctors jointly diagnosis difficult diseases.
</P>
<P>
In this way, those in frontier and remote areas are able to
receive better and more timely treatment.
</P>
<P>
Computers were put into use by the Chinese army in the early
1980s and mainly were used for command activities and military
drills.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the network played a vital role in saving the life of
Yang Xiaoxia, a young peasant girl from east China's Shandong
Province. Yang suffered from a rare disease that was causing
severe rotting of muscle and bone in her arm.
</P>
<P>
Unable to halt the disease, doctors with the General Hospital
of the Beijing Military Command sent the case to foreign
counterparts via the Internet. They received more than 300 pieces
of medical information about the disease.
</P>
<P>
The doctors then consulted with 60 Chinese specialists in
military and civil hospitals, only to find that the disease
resulted from several types of rare virus. Finally they succeeded
in curing the disease.
</P>
<P>
The case was listed as one of the 10 top news stories in the
country's medical science in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 728 Cases of Privatization Fraud Revealed in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Interior ministry has
uncovered 728 cases of fraud connected with Ukraine's
privatization process since January, a Ukrainian official said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sergy Pugachev, head of the ministry's main department for
combating economic crime, said abuse of office and forgery were
the two sources of corruption most damaging to the privatization
program.
</P>
<P>
Other common crimes were overstating the debts owed to
companies undergoing privatizaton, and understating the value of
companies' basic assets.
</P>
<P>
Citing one case, Pugachev said the director of a truck company
in the Vinnytsys Oblast had recently gone to trial for
underestimating the value of his company by 70 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
