<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Round of Iraq-UNSCOM Talks Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The second round of official
talks on Iraq's dismarment between Iraq and the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) started here Monday morning, Iraqi
News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz represented the Iraqi
side while Richard Butler, executive director of the UNSCOM on
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, headed the U.N.
side, according to the INA.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi side includes Oil Minister General Amir Mohammed
Rashid and Amir Al Saadi, adviser at the presidential office and
director of the Military Industrialization Organization, as well
as a number of experts of the Foreign Ministry and military
industry.
</P>
<P>
Aziz met Butler in the first round of the talks last night,
which lasted more than three hours at the headquarters of the
Foreign Ministry. The two sides refrained from making statements
on the results of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Aziz has informed Butler that he is going to hand the
U.N. chief arms inspector a report on Iraqi biological
weapons. Butler has said that he deems such a move a positive step
of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe the second round of the talks
focus on the delicate question of the entry of the U.N. arms
inspectors into the Iraqi presidential palaces which Iraq
considers as symbols of its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Butler will face difficulty in convincing the Iraqi leaders of
allowing the arms inspectors to enter the palaces, the observers
said.
</P>
<P>
So far, Iraq has been refusing to grant access to U.N. arms
inspectors to some sensitive sites, including presidential palaces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Wei Jianxing Meets Indian Vice-president </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Wei Jianxing, member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau and member of the
Secretariat of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), met here today with Indian Vice-president Krishna
Kant.
</P>
<P>
Wei arrived here yesterday on a nine-day goodwill visit to
India at the invitation of Kant.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, both sides agreed to increase friendly
exchanges between the two countries and further promote the
development of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kant said that Wei's visit is another top-level one to India by
a Chinese leader after President Jiang Zemin traveled to the South
Asian country in November last year.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang's visit has made important contributions to
promoting mutual understanding, friendship and cooperation between
the two countries, Kant said, adding that India and China have
made rapid progress in developing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that India believes it is in the interests of both
countries for India to build up a close, mutually beneficial and
friendly cooperative relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Five Principles of Peaceful Coexistence
jointly initiated by India and China, Kant stressed that these are
still applicable, adding that it is conducive to peace and
stability in Asia and the world as a whole to develop
Indian-Chinese friendship on the basis of these principles.
</P>
<P>
Kant said the governments and peoples of the two countries
should make joint efforts to push their friendly cooperation to a
new high.
</P>
<P>
Wei said that China and India have made great progress in
recent years in developing bilateral relations in the fields of
politics, economy, culture, and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"Friendship and cooperation have become the mainstream of
Sino-Indian relations," he said, adding that the two countries
share common views on peace and development and many other
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Although some issues left over by history between the two
countries remain to be resolved and bilateral economic and trade
ties need further expansion, Wei said, China and India, both with
long and splendid civilizations, can undoubtedly bring a
constructive partnership into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Wei said his current trip is aimed at deepening mutual
understanding, promoting friendship and increasing mutual trust
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On behalf the CPC and the Chinese government, Wei invited Kant
to visit China at his convenience and the Indian vice-president
thanked the Chinese side for the invitation.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were Dai Bingguo, head of the
International Department of the CPC Central Committee, and Pei
Yuanying, Chinese ambassador to India.  
