<HEADLINE> Moscow Thirsty for Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Minister without
Protfolio Yevgeny Yasin Monday predicted that foreign investments
to Russia may reach 100 billion U.S. dollars in the six or seven
years to come.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Russian regions' council on foreign
political and economic relations, Yasin said that foreign
investments will be made "chiefly in the fuel and energy sectors
and automobile industry where large-scale projects are already
underway or planned."
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in Russia are very nominal at present, the
minisiter said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the world financial crisis has had a negative
impact on foreign investments in Russia. The outflow of foreign
capital from Russia as a result of the crisis was estimated at 5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yasin believed this capital will gradually come back as the
country's financial situation stabilizes and industrial production
grows.
</P>
<P>
He estimated the Russia's GDP may increase by two percent and
inflation will stay within 5-8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said that the aerospace, nuclear energy and engineering
industries and energy equipment manufacture are Russia's most
promising and competitive industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
