<HEADLINE> Reform Aims at Agricultural Industrialization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Pilot work has officially begun
for a national reform of agriculture, which aims to turn
traditional farming into a modern industry.
</P>
<P>
This was the topic at an ongoing national symposium on
agricultural industrialization in E'zhou City in central China's
Hubei Province. Ten ministries and commissions directly under the
State Council, including the State Commission for Restructuring
the Economy and the Ministry of Agriculture, will take charge of
the effort.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-nine units nationwide will undergo three years of
experiment.
</P>
<P>
The pilot project will cover such aspects as the construction
of a modern agricultural enterprise system and rural cooperative
organizations, and reform of the circulation system for major
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The state will issue preferential policies in terms of credit,
project arrangement, taxation and land use to help key
agricultural enterprises become market-oriented
businesses. Qualified enterprises can also be listed on the stocks.
</P>
<P>
Rural cooperative economic organizations are expected to serve
as a bridge among farmers, enterprises and local governments,
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
