<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Stresses Importance of Advancing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai stressed today that advancing the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process is more important than drawing a
map on the further redeployments and permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai was making the comments when he briefed the
Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee on the
defense and security establishment's position on further troop
redeployments in the West Bank and the impending final-status
talks with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The minister said that any decision made by the cabinet should
be based on both the security map and the map of national
interests, but the more important thing is to push forward the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the remarks following the first deliberation
held Sunday by Israeli Cabinet on the planned second redeployment
in the West Bank and guidelines on permanent talks with the
Palestinians. Due to inner split over the so-called map of
national interests in the West Bank, the cabinet failed to reach a
solution.
</P>
<P>
During the seven-hour marathon session chaired by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, the ministers reviewed two maps of
Israeli interests presented by Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
and National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, which differed
on the definition of two security zones designed to provide
national security.
</P>
<P>
In his map, Sharon proposed creating two security zones to
ensure Israel's security: one 10-15 kilometer zone east of the
Green Line to divide Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas,
and another 20 kilometer-wide zone along the Jordan River.
</P>
<P>
Sharon also called for retaining control over the water
sources and all Jewish settlements in the West Bank. Netanyahu
is reportedly in favor of Sharon's map.
</P>
<P>
But Mordechai, in his so-called security map which was
drawn by the defense and security establishment, recommended
narrowing the two security zones into three to six kilometers
and seven to 10 kilometers respectively.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is to reconvene Tuesday in a bid to draw a
final map for Netanyahu to present to United States Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright when they meet in Paris Thursday.
The U.S. government has been pressing Israel hard to produce a
more credible and significant plan on further redeployments in
order to advance the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
A poll conducted by Israel Radio today showed that most
Israelis hoped the government will produce a detailed redeployment
plan in time for Netanyahu to present to Albright. Among the
polled, 71 percent people thought that Netanyahu should give a
detailed map to Albright, while 63 percent believed that the
government's plan will satisfy the Americans.
</P>
<P>
Former Foreign Minister and Defense Minister Moshe Arens
criticized today the government for its handling of the
redeployment issue. He pointed out that the aim to draw a
map on the final settlement with the PNA should not be only
to satisfy the Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
