<HEADLINE> Symposium Opens on Yangtze River Development Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A three-day symposium on the
Strategy of Developing the Yangtze River Economic Belt opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 officials and scholars are attending the seminar
which is being jointly sponsored by the Territorial Land
Development and Regional Economic Institute under the State
Planning Commission, the Yangtze River Area Development Institute
and the Shanghai Pudong Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River Economic Belt covers seven provinces --
Sichuan, Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Anhui, Jiangsu and Zhejiang -- and
the municipalities of Shanghai and Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the area generated more than 4 trillion yuan in
industrial output, 42.86 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The area is playing a vital role in the country's economy, said
Yu Lizhong, director of the Yangtze River Area Development
Institute.
</P>
<P>
He said the cooperation and coordination among the seven
provinces and two cities are helpful to both the developed eastern
region and underdeveloped western part of the country, forming a
new structure in China's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
