<HEADLINE> Pak Chief Justice's Counsel Applies for Full Bench </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Counsel for Chief Justice of
Pakistan's Supreme Court Sajjad Ali Shah, who is under restraint,
applied formally today to the apex court for constituting a full
bench to hear the petitions challenging Sajjad's appointment as
Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
The counsel, Abdul Hafeez Pirzada, asked the apex court to
consider his application as soon as possible, the official
Associated Press of Pakistan said.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court, which comprises 17 judges, has formed a
10-member bench to hear the petitions against Sajjad, who was
restrained by a 10-member bench of the Supreme Court on December 2
from performing his judicial and executive functions as Chief
Justice.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, on November 26, the appointment of Sajjad as Chief
Justice was suspended by the Quetta Bench of the apex court, which
said Sajjad was not the senior most judge of the Supreme Court at
the time of his appointment.
</P>
<P>
Ajmal Mian, the second senior most judge of the Supreme Court,
has been appointed by the government as Acting Chief Justice of
the apex court.  
</P>
