<HEADLINE> Vietnam Reaps More Rice Despite Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Vietnam's Mekong
Delta, the country's biggest rice bowl, harvested 500,000 more
tons of rice in 1997 than in the previous year, the Vietnam News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Seven Mekong Delta provinces each harvested more than one
million tons of rice this year despite the delayed receding flood
waters during the winter-spring crop and the damage caused by
tropical storm Linda last month.
</P>
<P>
Localities' figures showed that the total rice output rose by
800,000 tons for the winter-spring crop while the summer-autumn
output saw a drop due to a declining rice plantation area and
yield.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Ca Mau province, severely-stricken by tropical storm
Linda, brought home a total of nearly 746,000 tons of rice.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam rice export in the first 11 months of the year reached
3.3 million tons, and another 300,000 tons are expected to be
exported by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The total export volume will be 600,000 tons more than that of
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
