<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Applies Gene Engineering in Crop Disease Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are
developing genetically engineered crops for the prevention and
treatment of plant diseases.
</P>
<P>
Today's Science and Technology Daily reported that China now is
developing 47 kinds of genetically engineered plants which involve
62 kinds of pest control genes.
</P>
<P>
Huang Dafang, researcher at the Chinese Academy of Agricultural
Sciences, said at a national symposium on plant protection that
China's first generation of unpaired-gene, anti-pest cotton is
undergoing a trial growth period.
</P>
<P>
He said nine provinces including Anhui, Shanxi, Shandong and
Henan have experimented with the anti-pest cotton on 566 hectares
of demonstration land.
</P>
<P>
Huang added that the second paired-gene, anti-pest cotton has
also entered a trial planting period.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists also utilized gene engineering in raising
wheat yield by 20 percent on experimental land by successfully
controlling a major wheat disease.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, agricultural gene engineering is in its basic
research period and cannot be counted upon to resolve crop
production problems in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
