<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Criticized for not Cooperating with War-Crime Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Louise Arbour, the general
prosecutor for the Hague International Tribunal hearing war crimes
in ex-Yugoslavia, Monday criticized France for not cooperating
with the tribunal in providing evidence.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily, Liberation, Arbour said France
bans its military officers who served in peace-keeping forces in
ex-Yugoslavia from testifying before the court in person.
</P>
<P>
The Serb war criminals "feel absolutely safe" in the zone
controlled by French troops serving in the multi-national
stabilization force (SFOR) in Bosnia, she said.
</P>
<P>
Arbour expressed the same dissatisfaction in an interview with
the daily, Le Monde, last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Invited by French human rights groups, Arbour will visit Paris
Monday and meet with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and
Defense Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between the tribunal and France was made public
last week when French Defense Minister Alain Richard blamed the
tribunal for holding a "spectacle trial" by summoning French
peacekeepers in ex-Yugoslavia to the court to testify.
</P>
<P>
The French foreign ministry said last Friday that about 30
French military people had been summoned by the tribunal to
testify before the court.
</P>
<P>
But Paris would only allow these people to testify through
written statements rather than appearing in court in person, the
ministry noted.
</P>
<P>
The Le Monde said that in the dispute, a cultural conflict
could be observed.
</P>
<P>
The French military people were trained to remain silent rather
than speak in public, while questioning and answering in public
trials was a practice of the Anglo-Saxon judicial system, said the
daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
