<HEADLINE> PNG Leader Announces Major Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG) Prime
Minister Bill Skate today announced a major cabinet reshuffle to
shore up the credibility of his frequently changing coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Skate pulled off a major coup by persuading former Prime
Minister Rabbie Namaliu to join as his senior minister for state,
the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Only two weeks ago Rabbie called for Skate to stand aside and
for an inquiry into bribery allegations against the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Rabbie said today that he had accepted the post in the national
interest and he congratulated Skate for bringing men of quality
and integrity into the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"I have accepted the prime minister's invitation to serve in
the ministry because I believe the national interest must be
paramount at this difficult and demanding time in our nation's
development," he was quoted by AAP as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet reshuffle followed two weeks of political turmoil
which culminated in the expulsion of PNG's oldest party, Pangu,
from the government yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Skate had accused Pangu leader and former Deputy Prime Minister
Chris Haiveta of orchestrating bribery allegations against him.
</P>
<P>
Although Skate and Haiveta publicly reconciled last week, the
prime minister said yesterday that he had dismissed Pangu and its
seven ministers for disloyalty and for not supporting his
government.
</P>
<P>
The ministries in the Skate government now number 29 with some
realigned and new ones created.
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister Iairo Lasaro has been moved to the new
post of treasurer while the founder of Skate's People's National
Congress party, Dibara Yagabo, took over the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Skate has put himself in charge of the important defense
portfolio while former Defense Minister Mao Zeming has become
minister for housing.
</P>
<P>
Roy Yaki, who was fired by Skate two months ago as finance
minister for incompetence and for jeopardizing PNG's relationship
with China by attending a trade conference in Taiwan, has been
appointed foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Former Transport and Aviation Minister Philemon Embel has got
the crucial mining and energy portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Former deputy opposition leader Masket Iangalio, who joined the
government last week after forming a new Resources Action Party
made up of Highlands MPs, has taken over as the petroleum and gas
minister.
</P>
<P>
Skate, who claims now to have the support of 70 MPs in the
109-seat parliament, said his government is now entering a new era
of leadership and stability.
</P>
<P>
"We are at the crossroads now," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we do not take the tough decisions now, our nation and
people will continue to face difficult times ahead."
</P>
<P>
Skate said the new team would spend the next few weeks
preparing programs for the next budget due to be delivered in
March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
