<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Official Urges Sino-Portuguese JLG to Quicken Working Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-Portuguese Joint
Liaison Group (JLG) should step up its working process in the
remaining two years to properly resolve major issues concerning
Macao's smooth transition and handover, a top Chinese official
said.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua on the two-year countdown
before the handover of power to China on December 20, 1999, Han
Zhaokang, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
Sino-Portuguese JLG, said both sides should work more efficiently
to lay a solid foundation for the long-term stability and
development of Macao.
</P>
<P>
"In the last two years of transition, we should have a strong
sense of historic responsibility in facing and resolving the large
number of complicated issues," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
A big gap still exists between progress in the localization of
the civil service, the localization of law and the use of Chinese
as an official language and the actual needs of a smooth
transition and handover, the Chinese ambassador noted.
</P>
<P>
And talks on issues crucial to the smooth handover, like the
transfer of archives and assets and the pension of retired civil
servants, have either just started, or never been touched, or been
stalemated.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a number of new issues have been added to the
working agenda of the JLG.
</P>
<P>
Han said, however, that he remains optimistic about the
handling of these issues so long as the two sides abide by the
joint declaration and principles of the Basic Law of Macao,
respect and trust each other and start from the long-term and
overall interests of Macao and the long-term friendship between
China and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the need to improve the working pace, Han also
noted that certain progress has been made on the three leading
issues of transition -- the localization of the civil service, the
localization of law and the use of Chinese as an official
language.
</P>
<P>
Most of the lower-ranking civil posts have been localized and
the first Chinese director of a government department assumed
office last month. The Portuguese side promised to have all senior
and middle-ranking posts basically localized by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Law and the Code of Criminal Procedure, out of the
five leading laws in Macao, have been localized following
consultations in the JLG. Most laws enacted after 1990 have had
Chinese language versions, and a dozen local residents have been
appointed judges and procurators.
</P>
<P>
The use of Chinese as an official language has also scored
progress in the administrative, legislative and judiciary
departments of the Macao government, he noted.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, more efforts are still needed in handling the
three leading issues, especially, the localization of senior and
middle-ranking civil posts and the localization of the remaining
leading laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
