<HEADLINE> Interview: Canadian Business School Favors Hong Kong by Wang Qun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's leading business
school, the Richard Ivey School of Business, plans to open a small
campus here next August, offering Hong Kong business executives
Master of Business Administration (MBA) program at their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Dr. Paul Beamish, director of
Ivey's Asian Management Institute, spoke of Hong Kong's prominence
in the school's Asian commitment.
</P>
<P>
The campus will be the first Asian establishment for Ivey,
which celebrates its 75th anniversary this year.
</P>
<P>
An MBA program offered by a Western business school is not new
in Hong Kong, but the Ivey program is unique, he noted.
</P>
<P>
With classes fixed at Tuesday and Thursday evenings and
Saturday, the two-year program will allow business executives to
receive training without quitting their jobs.
</P>
<P>
And the program will be taught by "the best of Ivey staff"
based in Hong Kong, compared with some other Western MBA programs
here which are taught by "second-tier staff", Dr. Beamish noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the program will be "supported by business cases
developed specifically for Asia". Case study helps people develop
solid analytical and integrative skills for problem solving.
</P>
<P>
As the world's second largest producer of business cases after
Harvard, Ivey has produced about 80 cases with Asian relevance and
plans to produce 30 to 40 more next year.
</P>
<P>
One of the first priorities of Beamish's newly-established
Asian Management Institute is to develop Asian business cases.
</P>
<P>
He spoke of reasons why Hong Kong, ahead of other parts of
Asia, sees the first Ivey program in the region.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a broad base of alumni of Ivey, and their support
helps bring the program into place, while on the other hand Hong
Kong is an international business center where executive MBA
training is highly demanded.
</P>
<P>
"After the handover, everybody still wants good education.
Those values don't change at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a regular visitor to Hong Kong, Beamish said he "hasn't seen
big change here."
</P>
<P>
But he noticed "additional pride" in local people. "They are
proud of being part of China."
</P>
<P>
"Now the program is progressing smoothly," Dr. Beamish said.
</P>
<P>
Office space has been rented at a commercial building near
Victoria Park, with two Canadian staff members and three local
employees making preparations for the small campus, which includes
classrooms, lecture rooms and a library.
</P>
<P>
The first intake is about 35 students, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
