<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
decline sharply on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits
Times Industrials Index lost another 32.34 points to close at
1600.64 today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers here said share prices were dragged down by Asia's
persistent economic crisis. They added that fear of Singapore
banks' exposure to the regional crisis deepened and a perception
grew that the country's economy could not escape Asia's slowdown
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
They noted that electronics stocks also succumbed to selling on
the expectation that the global electronics industry was running
out of steam.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 182.79 million units, valued
at 443.94 million Singapore dollars (about 269.05 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 305 to 38 while 265
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Technologies Engineering was the most actively
traded stock as it registered a turnover of 17.21 million units.
It was followed by Rekapac which had 10.25 million shares traded.
Asian Food and Property (AFP) was next with 7.01 million shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1 dollar to finish at 21.5 Singapore
dollars. Roth S. increased by 25 cents to end at 8.6 Singapore
dollars. Times Publishing gained 14 cents to close at 3.16
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign
was the biggest loser of the day as it declined by 2.2 dollars to
end at 13.8 Singapore dollars. Roth M. fell by 1.2 dollars to
close at 13 Singapore dollars while Bukit Sembawang and the OCBC
(Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation) Foreign dropped by 70 cents
each to finish at 11.8 and 9.7 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
