<HEADLINE> Outlook on China's Auto Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, 18 to 20
million automobiles will be running on the roads in China, of
which 6 million are cars, and the demand for automobiles in the
year will be 2.5 to 3 million, and the farmers will need about
four million, the Overseas Edition of People's Daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
More individuals will buy cars by that time and government
departments, businesses and organizations will no longer the major
buyers at the auto market.
</P>
<P>
Cars have entered some relatively affluent families, and many
more families are ready to buy cars. Many believe automobiles
will be first to enter rural families.
</P>
<P>
China will soon introduce a new set of rules on automobile
scrapping and will offer favorable policies to encourage
the upgrading of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Chinese automobiles were exported to 85
countries and regions in 1995 and the 1994 auto export volume
reached 400 million U.S. dollars. China expects to export 350,000
to 400,000 automobiles by the year 2010 and hopes to earn five
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, imported cars dropped to 35 percent of the total at
China's market from 60.1 percent in 1994 and with the development
of the No. 1, No. 2, Shanghai and Tianjin automobile groups,
Chinese automobiles will eventually dominate the domestic
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
