<HEADLINE> Residential Housing Selling Well In North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
Province has sold nearly four-fifths of its residential housing to
individual buyers this year, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Cai, director of the Provincial Housing Reform Office, said
that the province now leads the country in residential housing
sales, with 78 percent of its residential housing, more than 100
million sq. m. of floor space, having been sold by the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
Shijiazhuang, the provincial capital, sold 14.4 million
sq.m. of housing, more than 80 percent of which was residential
housing.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that Hebei has done well in its housing reforms
since the province made people more enthusiastic about owning
their own house when the rent went from 0.2 yuan per sq.m. at the
start of 1990s to the present 1.2 yuan per sq.m., Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"Rent will further increase to 1.6 yuan next year to narrow the
gap between the rent and the sale price," the director said.
</P>
<P>
The province has finished 18 million sq.m. of residential
housing projects this year. Per capita floor space in cities and
towns is above 10 sq.m., the standard for relatively comfortable
living in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
