<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed slightly higher after a mixed day's trade highlighted by
futures-led buying at midday, as investors continued to look for
further leads from Asia and the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones broker Philip Toop said there had been
some switching between resource and industrial stocks throughout
the day.
</P>
<P>
"I think there's still concern about resource stocks and people
are buying into industrials for more stable earnings," Toop said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished up 6.9 points at 2,500.9.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP was the hardest hit of the heavyweights,
with its shares finishing 58.1 cents lower at 12.659 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
BHP releases its half-yearly results this week, with lower
copper and commodity prices expected to bite into its earnings and
analysts tipping a net pre-abnormal profit of around 369 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
During today's session, ratings agency Standard and Poor's
affirmed its short- and long-term ratings for BHP but revised the
company's outlook to negative from stable.
</P>
<P>
Toop said the troubles affecting Asian markets had raised
concerns amongst investors about the price of commodities falling
and a subsequent negative impact on resource stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 15.1 points to 1,041.0.
</P>
<P>
Amongst other resource stocks, global miner Rio Tinto was down
19.4 cents to 16.656 Australian dollars, and mining company WMC
was up 5.9 cents to 4.75 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks were mixed and trading in Sydney gold bullion
closed at 283.45 Australian dollars an ounce, down 40 U.S. cents
on yesterday's close of 283.85 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished the day 31.9 points higher
at 4,326.7.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, which finished up 37.6 points at
5,267.9, National Australia Bank added 22.9 cents to 20.369
Australian dollars while ANZ bank shed 13 cents to 9.92 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank rose 8.5 cents to 9.235 Australian dollars and the
Commonwealth Bank increased 20 cents to 16.90 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
