Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Louise Arbour, general prosecutor of the international
tribunal in the Hague in charge of judging the war crimes in
former Yugoslavia, has accused France of showing contempt to the
court by banning French officers from making testimony on war
crimes other than through written statements. She said that the
criminals sought by the court "feel safe" in the zone controlled
by French troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union (EU) summit in Luxembourg held on December
12-13 decided to start next Spring negotiations on adhesion to the
union with five central and eastern European countries -- Estonia,
Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Slovenia -- and Cyprus, thus
definitely putting an end to the division of the continent.
Meanwhile, Turkey announced on Sunday the cutting of all political
dialogue with EU, its refusal to participate in "European
conference" and the continuation of the integration into Turkey of
the northern part of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The 30th summit of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) held since last Saturday in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, is
dominated by the financial crisis which is acting ruthlessly in this
region of the world. Malaysia criticized the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) for its austerity remedies which it said is not
efficient. Meanwhile, new demonstrations took place on Saturday in
Seoul, South Korea, by protesters calling for a renegotiation of the
agreement with IMF. 
