<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Reform, Republic, Native Title is 1998 Focus for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government was ready to tackle a series of important policy
changes involving tax reform, the republic and native title in
1998, Prime Minister John Howard said today.
</P>
<P>
In a wide-ranging speech at a Sydney luncheon attended by about
100 ruling party faithful and some government ministers, Howard
reaffirmed his government's commitment to overhauling Australia's
tax system next year because the country's personal income tax
rates remained too high.
</P>
<P>
"It's going to be a year of very important policy changes,"
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"You can't put tax reform off forever, there's no way you can
do that," he said. "Sooner or later a government is going to have
to face the responsibility of tackling it."
</P>
<P>
The main focus for the government next year would include
holding a constitutional convention and developing a workable
model for an Australian republic, Howard said.
</P>
<P>
A constitutional convention is scheduled to take place early
next year to decide whether Australia will become a republic or
not by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
There was also the "difficult issue" of native title which has
yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The Howard government struggled, but failed last month to push
through parliament a bill on native title in a bid to limit or
extinguish the right of the aboriginal people to claim the land
being used by pastoralists, miners and farmers.
</P>
<P>
The government warned that the bill, made in response to the
High Court's ruling that native title and pastoral leases could
co-exist, could eventually be used to trigger an early election by
dissolving parliament if the Senate vetoes it or heavily amends it
after it is tabled for the second time early next year.
</P>
<P>
The miners, farmers and pastoralists, who have been calling for
extinguishment of native title, and the aborigines, who have
accused the government of discriminating against them, are not
satisfied with the government's bill.
</P>
<P>
With the challenges ahead, the prime minister said: "There's an
enormous amount that's on our plate and on the agenda for the
coming year."
</P>
<P>
He said Australia's greatest achievement this year was its
success in remaining virtually unscathed by the recent Asian
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he was pleased that his government's policies to
promote employment were also starting to bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
"We have tried very hard to lay the proper foundations for that
and we are starting to see that some of the foundations we have
laid are starting to work."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Urges Enhanced Cooperation Among East Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin Monday called for enhanced cooperation among East Asian
countries to ensure the interests of the peoples in the region and
promote peace and development of mankind.
</P>
<P>
Jiang issued the call in a speech on the first informal summit
of China, Japan, the Republic of Korea and the nine members of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We should intensify economic and technological cooperation,
especially hi-tech cooperation, set up a rational economic
structure in the region and bring about a non-exclusive and
non-discriminative model of economic cooperation..." Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He described the cooperation as one that can "facilitate
countries to make up for their deficiencies by drawing upon
other's advantages and strike a balance among different interests."
</P>
<P>
Jiang said East Asia in today's world is a force that cannot be
ignored politically, economically, culturally and geographically.
</P>
<P>
He said countries in the region should uphold the principles of
mutual respect, equal participation, mutual benefit and common
development in their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the countries to engage in friendly dialogues
and consultations to build up confidence, broaden agreement, seek
common ground while putting aside differences, and address
differences properly so as to ensure regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president expressed his belief that East Asian
countries can, through their own development and mutual
cooperation, provide useful experience and set a model for
economic cooperation among countries and regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, they can also play an important role in
promoting the establishment of a just and rational new
international political and economic order of peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
