<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Urged to Investigate POWs Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian students from Tehran
University have urged the United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan to have a faster investigation into the issue of prisoners
of war (POW) of the Iran-Iraq war (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
Local daily Iran News reported today that the students made
their request in a letter to the U.N. chief. However, the
daily did not specify when the letter was delivered to Annan.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, the students appealed Annan to send special
delegation to gear up the release of Iranian POWs who are allegely
still detained in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
They accused the Iraqi government of not cooperating in
releasing Iranian POWs in Iraq despite existing documents prove
the presence of Iranian POWs in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
They said that Iran has sent different delegations to Iraq to
investigate the case of Iranian POWs but Iraq has not taken any
measures in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has claimed that about 15,000 Iranian POWs are still
kept in Iraq, but Baghdad said that there is no Iranian POWs in
Iraq but 62 detainees captured in 1991. Iraq also blamed Iran for
holding more than 18,000 Iraqi POWs.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the Eighth Islamic summit held here last
week, Iraqi Vice President Yassin Ramadan reiterated Baghdad's
stance on the POWs issue, though expressing its readiness to
improve relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan held several talks with senior Iranian officials
including Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and First Vice
President Hassan Habibi, hoping that the remaining issues between
the two neighbors would be solved in the near future in order to
pave the way for normalization of bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
