<HEADLINE> Islamic Leader Cut Short Visit After Receiving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- "The Nation of Islam" leader
 Louis Farrakhan has cut short his visit to Jerusalem and left for
Jordan after receiving death threats from Jewish extremists.
</P>
<P>
Farrakhan, also a U.S. black leader, is scheduled to hold
noon prayers today at Al-Aqsa Mosque in East Jerusalem, but
has to cut short his visit after receiving death threats from
Jewish extremists in the morning and now is on his way to
Jordan, the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) announced.
</P>
<P>
Farrakhan has caught Israeli officialdom off guard when he
showed up on Sunday at the Allenby Bridge between Jordan and
the West Bank. He was the guest of the PNA, but he told
the Israeli security officials at the border checkpoint that he
hopes to visit Israel as well.
</P>
<P>
His intended visit to Israel was met with mixed attitudes
here. Israeli Foreign Ministry on Sunday ruled out any meeting
between him and Israeli officials "as long as he adheres to
vicious and hateful language against Israel, Judaism and the
Jewish people."
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Dan Naveh took a less diplomatic course and
called on Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Interior Minister
Eli Suissa to have Farrakhan expelled at once from Israel when
he enters the country.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's director of
communications David Bar-Illan said on Sunday that because
Farrakhan holds an American passport he is free to tour
Israel without hinderance.
</P>
<P>
But Farrakhan spent a busy day in the PNA territories on
Sunday. "During the Christmas season...it is my hope that this
troubled area in the world, that needs peace as much as
any part of the earth, will find peace and goodwill," he
told reporters in Ramallah before proceeding to Gaza for a
meeting with PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Arafat, he suggested that Israel is
to blame for the crisis in the peace talks and said U.S.
President Bill Clinton should apply more pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We stand firmly with the Palestinian people in its struggle
for justice...and I think the U.S. has a great role to
play...after all, billions of dollars of American tax payers'
money come to Israel each and every year and this should give
President Clinton enough leverage to insist that...the peace
process be put back on track," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Farrakhan said that people who are opposed have a right to
struggle, but added that it is unnecessary for any individual or
group to engage in any behavior that takes the lives of innocent
people for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
Farrakhan has been critical of some aspects of Jewish behavior
towards the black people and his frequent remarks disparaging
Jews and Judaism were not welcomed by Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
