<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Former Defense Chief Quits Party to Bid For </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Former Philippine Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa quit the ruling party today to continue
his bid to run for president in next year's elections despite
losing President Fidel Ramos' endorsement.
</P>
<P>
"I declare a rebellion against the traditional politics of
corrupt patronage and the idea that people and their principles
can be bought," the 63-year-old retired general said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
He also declared that he will form a third force with Manila
Mayor Alfredo Lim to compete in the presidential race in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, a joint statement issued by the two men did not
indicate the positions de Villa and Lim will respectively run for
in the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
"Today, I clearly state my refusal to cooperate and stand on
the same platform with party leaders whose ways I cannot stomach
anymore," de Villa said in the statement, defying Ramos and the
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
De Villa's move came a week after Ramos chose Jose de Venecia,
speaker of the House of Representatives, as the presidential
candidate of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party in the 1998 national
polls.
</P>
<P>
De Villa had bitterly competed with De Venecia to win the
party's endorsement and local reports had earlier predicted that
De Villa, a close friend of Ramos, would gain the blessing of the
president.
</P>
<P>
The former defense chief said at the weekend that he would
continue his presidential bid after a provincial tour in order to
consult the people on whether they still want him to run for
president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
