<HEADLINE> Ramos Expresses Regret over Former Defense Chief's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today asked former Defense Secretary Renato de Villa to
reconsider his decision to bolt from the ruling Lakas-NUCD party
and pursue his bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also belittled De Villa's chances of winning in next
year's elections without his backing and the machinery of the
ruling party, a statement released by the Presidential Palace
said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' statement came after De Villa's announcement earlier
today that he quit the ruling party to pursue his bid for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Ramos last week chose Jose de Venecia, Speaker of the House of
Representatives, as the man who will carry the ruling party's
banner in the May 11, 1998 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
De Villa, who joined the ruling party just four months ago, had
bitterly competed with De Venecia to win the president's blessing.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Rene de Villa and his followers will reexamine
their position in the light of their participation in and
commitments to the party's political processes and as well as the
chances of their success outside the administration party," said
Ramos, who is currently in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
Ramos expressed "regret" over the former defense secretary's
decision to run for president outside the ruling party because he
regards De Villa as a "man of integrity whose support is an asset
to the Lakas-NUCD", the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, De Venecia also issued a statement on the decision
of De Villa to bolt out of the ruling party, saying "We are
keeping the door of reconciliation open to former Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa and his dwindling band of supporters."
</P>
