<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tax Revenue Tops 666 Billion Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China collected a total of
61.457 billion yuan in industrial and commercial tax in November,
up 14 percent, or 7.569 billion yuan from the same 1996 period,
according to the State Administration of Taxation.
</P>
<P>
Another two major tax items under the new tax regime, the
value-added tax and consumption tax, posted an increase of 10.1
percent to reach 34.948 billion yuan last month.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, the state tax revenue during the past
eleven months totaled 666.087 billion yuan, up 18.1 percent,
or 102.21 billion yuan over the same 1996 period, meeting 95.8
percent of the annual tax collection target.
</P>
<P>
With the stamp tax on stock trading and the business tax on the
financial sector adjusted from the total amount, the revenue
increase stood at 15.1 percent, higher than the national economic
growth of about nine percent.
</P>
<P>
The revenue of business tax, income tax from the private
sector and overseas-funded ventures, and stamp tax have all
overfulfilled the yearly targets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the individual income tax surged 36 percent on a
yearly basis to 23.259 billion yuan during the period, meeting
96.9 percent of annual target.
</P>
<P>
The value-added tax and consumption tax, on the other hand,
amounted to 352.374 billion yuan during the eleven-month period,
up 10.8 percent on a yearly basis, compared to the targeted 19.3
percent of annual growth.
</P>
<P>
State taxation officials also pointed out that tax in arrears
still pose a serious problem, and at the end of November, the
value-added tax and consumption tax in default accounted for 73.2
percent of the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
