<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian PM Arrives on Official Visit to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin arrived here today for an official visit to Turkey to
enhance bilateral ties, including realizing multi-billion gas deal
plans and seeking a solution to the disputed straits.
</P>
<P>
The long-expected visit of Chernomyrdin came ahead of his
Turkish counterpart Mesut Yilmaz's forthcoming trip this week to
the United States after Turkey, an associate member of the
European Union (EU), was excluded Friday from the EU enlargement
process in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day visit, Chernomyrdin is expected to submit
Russia's request for Turkey to make some changes to the rules in
respects of traffic in the Turkish straits, the Bosphorus and the
Dardanelles.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Chernomyrdin said in Moscow Saturday that
Russia has been objecting to the Turkish self-policy of arranging
and implementing the rules for the straits.
</P>
<P>
The rules have already violated the Montreaux Straits Agreement
signed between Turkey and the former Soviet Union in 1936, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has long been opposing Turkey's limiting the number of
ships carrying oil through the straits in Turkey linking Asian
and European continents.
</P>
<P>
Turkey claims that if a huge number of oil tankers are allowed to
pass through these waterways, this will increase the possibility
of dangerous explosions in and around Istanbul, the largest city
of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Russian and Turkish prime ministers will also discuss some
important issues, including the controversial 150 kilometer-range
S-300 missiles, which are planned to be sold to Cyprus by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to hold talks on the controversial
Turkish-Russian natural gas deal -- the transportation of 16
billion cubic meters of Russian gas through an undersea pipeline
to pass via the Black Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
