<HEADLINE> Guangdong Foreign Trade Up 19.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province's foreign trade volume topped 100 billion US dollars in
the first ten months this year, up 19.7 percent from that of the
same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
According to the local customs, the province in the period
registered a trade volume of 103.8 billion dollars, of which
exports reached 60.2 billion dollars, up 27.2, while imports
totaled 43.6 billion dollars, an increase of 10.7 percent. The
aggregated trade surplus hit 16.6 billion dollars, or 16 percent
of the total foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said state enterprises contributed more to the
trade upsurge. Between January and October, the exports of state
enterprises reached 45.8 billion dollars, up 26.7 percent from the
same period of last year. The growth rate of exports in
enterprises with overseas investments was 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong remained the top trade partner for the province, with
a trade volume of 27.2 billion dollars. Other major partners
included the United States, Japan, the European Union, Taiwan, the
Republic of Korea, Singapore and Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
