<HEADLINE> Buddhist Jiuhua Mountain Attractive to Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Jiuhua Mountain, one of the four
Buddhist shrines in China, has attracted over three million
Chinese and overseas tourists and pilgrims so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The mountain in the southern part of Anhui Province became
known as a leading Buddhist mountain over 1,000 years ago after a
prince from Korea practised Buddhism in the mountain.
</P>
<P>
It became even more well-known after Li Bai, a noted Chinese
poet of the Tang Dynasty (618-907) had written over 50 poems in
praise of the beautiful scenery of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Anhui Provincial Government has made great
efforts in large-scale reconstruction of temples and sites of
historical interest.
</P>
<P>
As part of the efforts, a forest park, a lake natural reserve
and an "underground palace" composed of several karst caves have
been built and opened to tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
