<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building Tiger Breeding Base in Eastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The city of Suzhou in China's
Jiangsu Province has started building a breeding base for the
South China tiger on Lidao Island, to protect the rare species,
which is on the verge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
On its four hectares of land, the base now has 13 of the tigers
and plans to increase the number to 30 in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou Zoo has 14 South China tigers itself, the largest
number in China's zoos.
</P>
<P>
Since 1983, the zoo has produced 38 of the tigers in captivity,
29 of which have survived. It has sent 15 of them to zoos in the
cities of Tianjin, Guangzhou, Xiamen, and Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The South China tiger, or Xiamen tiger, is found only in
China. Chinese zoos have 50 of them.
</P>
<P>
The breeding base has gotten 280,000 yuan (34,000 US dollars)
for the base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
