<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on New Security Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Qian
Qichen said here today that if lasting peace is to be secured, it
is imperative to cultivate a new security concept and seek new
ways of maintaining peace.
</P>
<P>
"The security concept and the security regime of the Cold War
era, based on military alliances with ever escalating armament,
are in our view incapable of making peace," Qian noted.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is also China's foreign minister, made the remarks in
a speech delivered at a business forum titled "A Private Sector
Salute to ASEAN" here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Expanding military blocs run counter to the trend of the
times," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He outlined the following points to explain the new security
concept and new ways of maintaining peace:
</P>
<P>
-- State-to-state relations should be based on the five
principles of mutual respect for sovereignty and territorial
integrity, mutual non-aggression, non-interference in each other's
internal affairs, equality and mutual benefit, and peaceful
coexistence.
</P>
<P>
"This is the political basis and prerequisite for regional and
global security. In this regard, the cultivation of healthy and
stable relations among the world's major powers is crucial to
peace and security at both regional and global levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
-- Countries should step up mutually beneficial cooperation and
mutual opening-up in the economic sphere, do away with inequality
and discriminatory policies in economic and trade relations, and
pursue common prosperity by gradually narrowing the development
gap between nations.
</P>
<P>
The recent financial turmoil in Southeast Asia shows that
economic security is an important component of stability and
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To maintain a normal economic and financial order requires not
only a sound macro-economic management regime and a sound
financial system, but also greater regional and global financial
cooperation, concerted efforts to ward off the speculative attacks
by international hot money and creation of a stable and secure
external economic environment," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
-- Countries should enhance mutual understanding and trust
through dialogue and cooperation and undertake to resolve their
differences or disputes by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
This is the practical way of ensuring peace and security, he
said. "Security dialogue and cooperation should be aimed at
increasing trust instead of creating confrontation. It must not
be allowed to target at any third country, nor undermine the
security interest of other countries," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
