<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Stresses Peace for Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today that securer peace is
the precondition for economic development.
</P>
<P>
"Standing at the threshold of a new century, we can see quite
clearly that peace, development, stability and cooperation have
come to form the mainstream of our times," Qian said at a business
forum titled "A Private Sector Salute to ASEAN" here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Without peace, there can be no development to speak of," said
Qian, who is accompanying Chinese President Jiang Zemin to the
East Asian informal summit which began here today.
</P>
<P>
The rapid economic development in the Asia-Pacific, East Asia
in particular, owes itself mainly to the absence of any threat of
war as countries in the region have shown increasingly keen
political will to settle their disputes peacefully, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a favorable situation characterized by mutual
reinforcement between political stability and economic development
has taken shape by and large in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that shared interests and interdependence in the
economic field have promoted dialogue and cooperation among
nations and economic links and mutually-beneficial cooperation
have intertwined to form a network making for peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister agreed with Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir's view that national security is inseparable
from political stability, economic success and social harmony.
</P>
