<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yuan Unaffected by Currency Turmoils  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese yuan is widely
expected to remain stable next year despite recent currency
turmoils in some countries in Southeast and East Asia, officials
and experts said.
</P>
<P>
"China's foreign exchange supply will continue to exceed demand
at the domestic market next year, indicating that the yuan's
stable exchange rate will continue," an official of the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) said.
</P>
<P>
The country's good foreign trade situation, a large influx of
foreign capital and general expectation of a strong economy will
be the fundamental factors for the stable yuan, Tao Liming,
director of the International Finance Research Institute of the
Bank of China, told Xinhua in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Tao said that China will continue to enjoy a trade surplus in
1998, though the favorable balance will not be as big as that of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China had a trade surplus of 40.2
billion US dollars in the first 11 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tao acknowledged that the significant currency devaluation in a
number of Asian countries, including Thailand, the Philippines,
Indonesia and the Republic of Korea, will affect China's export of
labor intensive products such as shoes and garments in some
respects.
</P>
<P>
"But the impact will not be so great as to affect China's
overall trade balance," he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the continuous implementation of a moderately
tight fiscal and monetary policy means that imports will not surge
in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yuan Unaffected by Currency Turmoils (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"When factors affecting the trade balance are considered, China
will continue to enjoy a trade surplus, though not as large as
that of this year," Tao said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that foreign capital inflow into China will slow
down next year as investors will be more cautious in making
investment in Asia-Pacific countries as a result of the recent
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But due to the attractiveness of the Chinese market and
prospective dynamic Chinese economy, the absolute amount of
capital inflow into China will remain at a considerable level next
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, China's balance of international payments will
continue to be good next year, which guarantees a stable rate of
the yuan, Tao said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China's huge foreign exchange reserves, at 134
billion US dollars at the end of September, are a powerful support
for the stability of the yuan.
</P>
<P>
The SAFE official said that currency turbulence in the region
will not have any significant impact on the stability of the
yuan's value.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese yuan has been consolidating against major western
currencies since China unified its exchange rate in 1994. It
gained 0.3 percent against the US dollar last year, following
rises of 2.9 and 1.5 percent in 1994 and 1995, respectively. This
year it has been under constant pressure for appreciation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Boasts Promising Prospects of Geothermal Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Yangbajain Geothermal Power
Station in the Tibet Autonomous Region, the biggest of its kind in
China, has been operating well over the past 20 years and
contributed much to the local economy.
</P>
<P>
Since its first generating unit was launched into operation in
1977, the station has generated 1.1 billion kwh of electricity,
which accounted for about 45 percent of the electricity in the
Lhasa power network.
</P>
<P>
Yang Guangjiu, director of the station, said the geothermal
pressures in the current ten wells are dwindling after 20 years
of exploitation, but geothermal resources in deeper layers are
rather abundant.
</P>
<P>
A 1,000-meter well dugged out recently is able to gush out hot
water of 205 degrees Celsius, and it is the best geothermal well
in China. The hot gas from this well only can drive all the current
generating units, the director said.
</P>
<P>
"It shows that geothermal resources between 800 to 1,500 meters
underground are of great quality and quantity, and bigger
generating untis can be installed," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the health-promotion function of geothermal water
is attracting more people, and the sulphur-rich water is suitable
for detergent production, wool spinning and weaving, and pottery
making, the director said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
