<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nurses' Strike Enters 17th Day in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Kenya's
health sector remained grim with nurses in public hospitals
continuing their nationwide strike for the 17th day Sunday, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Many patients were unattended while some hospitals remained
closed, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The nurses launched the strike on November 28 to seek for up
to 500 percent pay rise. The Ministry of Health has dismissed the
demands as unrealistic, saying they outstripped its budget.
</P>
<P>
At the Kenyatta National Hospital, the biggest public hospital
in the capital city of Nairobi, doctors were busy attending to a
large number of patients at the casualty and the emergency units.
</P>
<P>
One of the doctors there said the hospital had recently
recruited more medical personnel to help cope with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"But the situation remains grim as the work is just too much
and they seem to be untrained," said the doctor.
</P>
<P>
In Nyeri in central Kenya, a middle-aged woman gave birth at a
bus station after she was turned away from the provincial general
hospital.
</P>
<P>
In Kisumu, the third-largest city in Kenya, the New Nyanza
General Hospital and the Kisumu District hospital were empty. All
the hospital gates remained locked as in-patients and
out-patients were turned away.
</P>
<P>
As the sick and the injured continue suffering, the
government, under more and more criticism for being "curiously
slow" in attempts to end the strike, has been urged to hold
negotiations with the nurses as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
