<HEADLINE> Zambia's Inter-Party Talks to Continue, Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's ruling party has said
the proposed inter-party dialogue will go ahead even without
opposition leaders like former Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted Michael Sata, national secretary
of the Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) as saying here
Sunday that Kaunda is not a party and his absence will not be
allowed to affect the time-table for the crucial talks.
</P>
<P>
Sata was reacting to a statement issued by Kaunda's United
National Independence Party (UNIP) last week that Kaunda will
attend the inter-party talks scheduled for next month if the
government guarantees his safe return from a marathon overseas
trip.
</P>
<P>
He said that Kaunda, who went abroad on the eve of the October
28 coup attempt, did not seek permission from anyone when leaving
the country and why he is now making his return an issue when the
agenda for the talks has already been set.
</P>
<P>
"If Kaunda does not want to attend the talks, we shall still
go ahead with the dialogue because he is not a political party.
We will stick by our program and will not wait for any president
who is not ready," Sata said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he rejected the inclusion of independent parliament
members into the dialogue, saying the talks are strictly for
representatives of political parties and independent candidates
merely represent their own opinions not anybody else's.
</P>
<P>
Two independent members have protested against being left out
of the dialogue initiative, arguing that it is unacceptable for
the government to exclude the 10 MPs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
