<HEADLINE> Shanghai Strengthens Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, will strengthen its efforts in controlling the
city's water, air and noise pollution next year, said Lu Shuping,
director of Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that the city's main pollution includes contaminated
water, car exhausts, and traffic noise.
</P>
<P>
The city aims to clear up the Suzhou River, running through the
urban area, reducing the daily release of waste water by 21,400
tons. The city also prohibits the construction of new fertilizer,
printing and electroplating plants in the suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
According to Lu, the city's daily capacity of sewage disposal
has reached 220 tons.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the city's residents are using coal
gas. And the city will build another five liquefied natural gas
filling stations, encouraging cars using gas instead of petroleum.
</P>
<P>
The city will also increase their public green areas by 300
hectares, and build three new parks.
</P>
<P>
So far, the city's green coverage has reached 17.8 percent, up
0.8 percentage point compared with last year. And the city's
average public green area have increased by 0.4 square meter to
2.3 square meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
