<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Coffee Exports in Modest Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Uganda coffee exports were in
modest recovery in November, the Uganda Coffee Development
Authority (UCDA) said in its monthly report.
</P>
<P>
Uganda exported 179,604 bags (60 kg for each bag) of coffee
worth of 16 million U.S. dollars last month, bringing a 37
percent increase in the quantity and 32 percent in the value,
comparing to the exports of 130,829 bags in October which worth
12 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Culminative coffee exports for October and September, the
first two months of the 1997-1998 coffee year, stood at 310,433
bags worth of 28 million dollars, while the country exported
792,839 bags of coffee worth of 62.9 million dollars during the
same period in last coffee year.
</P>
<P>
The UCDA report attributed the decrease this year in coffee
export to the El Nino phenomena. The extensive drought resulted
in the poor growth of coffee plants, and the prolonged rains in
the country in recent three months have delayed the harvest and
halted the trading.
</P>
<P>
The floods have made the movement of coffee trucks in coffee
areas impossible, and the coffee season may be delayed to April
1998, two months longer than the usual year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is the main export product for Uganda. It earns 65
percent of the country's foreign exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
