<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Rental Business In China Running Into Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- In spite of its increasing
popularity, the auto rental business in Fuzhou, the capital of
China's Fujian Province, still has a way to go.
</P>
<P>
The first auto rental agency opened in April, 1994, and the
service has grown more popular among the people of Fuzhou,
especially young professionals, who can afford the 300 to 400 yuan
per day for business trips and outings. The city's three agencies
have nearly 200 buses, vans, and cars, 80 percent of which are
rented on weekdays. On weekends and holidays, almost all are
reserved by customers.
</P>
<P>
But, the three renters have made very little profit in the
flourishing business. According to senior managers, it is hard for
the agencies to buy more automobiles because banks do not have a
mortgage loan policy for automobiles, and car manufacturers do not
finance auto purchases.
</P>
<P>
And, the auto leasers pay the same fees as taxi companies but
can't do similar business. They also have to take into account
confiscation of automobiles if they are used for illegal
activities into, and other risks.
</P>
<P>
One private businessman involved in the cosmetics business who
has spent 98,000 yuan for nearly 300 days of car use this year,
who was about to renew the rental contract for next year, said
that a rented car has many advantages. He has much less money tied
up and can get a new model easily. But, what is more important, he
doesn't have to worry about things like license plates,
maintenance, an annual inspection, and taxes.
</P>
<P>
But, even if there is a strong demand for cars, the rental
business is not something that is going to develop in a short
period of time, according to one agency's manager.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
