<HEADLINE> Fuel Transportation Difficult as Heavy Rains Lash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Road
Tanker's Association (TAROTA) has suspended the transportation of
fuel to the Lake Victoria region and neighboring Rwanda and the
Republic of Congo because a 10-km road section in the west Tabora
Region has been damaged by floods.
</P>
<P>
Floods have damaged the road between Igunga and Nzega, washing
away the Ulyang'ombe bridge on the road last weekend as heavy
rains continued falling in Igunga District, "The Guardian" said
today.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,600 people have been made homeless in the district, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
TAROTA Chairman Faisal Awadh said here on Sunday that about
150 transit fuel tankers have been stranded in Tabora for the
past two weeks because the heavy rains have made the road
impassable.
</P>
<P>
Awadh called on the government to repair the road stretch
immediately. "It is difficult to use the road even on foot,"
observed Awadh, whose association is responsible for
transportation of fuel to different upcountry destinations and
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that by the end of this week the Mwanza Airport
and other major facilities will start experiencing fuel shortage.
</P>
<P>
However, the TAROTA chairman commended the government for
taking measures to control fuel smuggling by unscrupulous dealers
from Kisumu in Kenya through Lake Victoria to Mwanza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
