<HEADLINE> Tibet Speeds Up Telecommunications Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region is
accelerating development of its telecommunications services by
using foreign and domestic loans.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, two major telecommunications programs were completed
and went into operation in Lhasa City, capital of the region, and
other three cities and prefectures.
</P>
<P>
One of the programs involved a 4.77 million U.S. dollar loan
from the Australian government to construct a program-controlled
telephone system with 30,000 lines in the west section of Lhasa
City.
</P>
<P>
The other program is to update satellite telecommunication
equipment in four cities and prefectures -- Lhasa, Nyingchi, Qamdo
and Ngari -- by using a mixed loan of 8.85 million U.S. dollars
from the Canadian government.
</P>
<P>
According to the Tibet Telecommunications Administration, the
region has used another batch of loans of 7.5 million dollars to
introduce 25 micro-wave controlled telephone systems.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Zhongyi, director of the administration, said that so far
construction of 10 systems has been completed, which made 107
townships connected with the region's telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
The region is now using a mixed loan of five million
U.S. dollars from the Canadian government and 60 million yuan from
domestic banks in the region and the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications to update telecommunication equipment in Lhasa
City as well as Xigaze and Shannan prefectures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
