<HEADLINE> North China Port City Becoming New Mini-Car Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a leading port city
in north China, is becoming a rising production base of mini-cars
and mini-vans, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjin Automobile Industry Group, the only auto maker in
Tianjin after acquiring 30-odd small car plants, turned out 134,000
cars in the first 10 months of this year, up five percent over
the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Its sales value in the first 10 months exceeded 10 billion
yuan, ranking itself among behemoths in China.
</P>
<P>
It has an annual production capacity of 230,000 automobile, of
which 150,000 are mini-cars.
</P>
<P>
The group has built 23 joint ventures in seven countries and
regions for producing spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Minis, with 1.0-liter engines, are autos more affordable for
Chinese families. Statistics show that 70,000 minis sold in
Beijing this year, 90 percent were purchased by individuals.
</P>
