<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly In North China City Cling To Traditional Ways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A study in north China's
Tianjin Municipality has shown that 94.3 percent of the elderly
want to be taken care of by their family members when they become
ill or too old to work.
</P>
<P>
Among the 541 people surveyed, all above the age of 65, 31.9
percent said that they want their spouses to take care of them,
whereas 36.1 percent and 24.9 percent of the elders surveyed chose
their married sons and daughters, and the remaining 7.1 percent
chose their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that 43.1 percent of them live with
their family members, and only 7.3 percent pay their own daily
expenses.
</P>
<P>
The results are similar to those surveys carried out in the
city in 1984 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 77.3 percent said they unbosom themselves to their
spouses when they have problems and are unhappy, while 74.9
percent talk with their children.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 75.8 percent said that they don't
feel lonely because their children care for them and, even if they
do not live with their children, the latter often visit them or
call them by the phone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
