<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Village Doctors Take Care of Farmers in Remote Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Even in the most remote part
of southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, farmers are
able to consult doctors in their own villages when they sick,
local health sources said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 95 percent of the region's 14,756 villages
have their own doctors.
</P>
<P>
The two or three doctors in each of the villages are
responsible for treatment of common diseases, epidemic prevention
and health care for women and children.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight-year-old Yi Wenhui heads a clinic in Qingshui
village in Hepu county. A graduate from the Guangxi College of
Traditional Chinese Medicine, Yi said that all the four doctors of
the clinic have a degree from a secondary medical school or above,
and licenses issued by the county health department.
</P>
<P>
"The county health department sponsors regular training courses
to improve our medical skills," Yi noted.
</P>
<P>
The courses include bimonthly meetings for doctors to exchange
their views on how to prevent and treat common diseases, according
 to local conditions, and annual courses for the doctors to
further improve their medical skills.
</P>
<P>
The village clinic doctors offer 24-hour service a day, said
villager Chen Chengji.
</P>
<P>
"Without the village clinic," he said, "we have to cycle for an
hour to the township clinic in case we are sick, and it will take
at least half a day for one to visit the doctor."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Yi is quite confident of his medical skill. "The villagers
always come to us first when they are ill, and we can treat most
of the common diseases," he said, adding that the village doctors
seldom send patients to larger hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
