</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Despite a surging economy and low unemployment,
demand for emergency food and shelter continued to grow this year,
according to a survey by the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
Among the reasons, officials said, are low wages and high
housing costs. Nearly all the cities expected demand for food and
shelter to rise next year. (U.S.-Poverty-Survey)
