<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nepal's Political Instability Hurts Economic  Development  by Yi Aijun, Chen Anning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Political instability in
Nepal, one of the poorest countries in the world, has affected the
country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayan kingdom has seen seven governments in power since
1990.
</P>
<P>
After a hung parliament emerged in the mid-term elections in
November 1994, things became even more tricky in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Since no single party commands a simple majority in the
parliament, Nepal's coalition politics has been marred by
struggles over petty interests which drove parties to change
partners frequently.
</P>
<P>
Three coalition governments have been born in the past three
years in Nepal, two in this year alone.
</P>
<P>
Frequent government changes affect Nepal's economic development
in many ways, said Dr. Kishor Kumar Guru-Gharana of the National
Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Political instability causes policy instability, which in turn
leads to macro-economic instability, he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said as the system in Nepal is still a highly centralized
one, every time political instability happens, government
officials have to wait until the situation becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
And every time there is a change of government, not only the
prime minister and ministers, but also the secretaries, project
directors and engineers are changed. All of them have to take time
to study new things and all these delay decision-making, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 90 percent of the country's projects and programs
have been affected. And on the average, there is a delay of two
years in the implementation of the projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This affects foreign investment as well as domestic
investment," said Dr. Guru-Gharana.
</P>
<P>
According to a world investment report, Nepal gets only 2
million U.S. dollars of investment every year.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Nepal's economic situation has been very
discouraging, the U.S.-trained economist said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nepal's annual economic growth has been low
at 4.5 percent in recent years, and exports have been declining,
including carpet and garment, the country's major foreign exchange
earners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports are growing at a slower pace than before.
"In other countries, this is a good sign. But in Nepal, not good.
Because most of our industries are based on imported raw
materials, machinery and petroleum products. It means the economy
is slack, and the industries are slack," the economist said.
</P>
<P>
Sluggish imports lead to reduction of tax revenue, which is
based heavily on imports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many Nepalese have become tired of the political antics in the
country and said they wanted the country to be put on the right
track of economic development, as 45 percent of the country's
population of 21.6 million are still living below the poverty
line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Science Getting Greater Role In China's Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China will place greater
importance on science and technology in agriculture because the
farmland acreage and water resources per capita are much lower
than the world's average, according to an article in today's
"People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
The article by the Ministry of Agriculture says that China's
population will be 1.6 billion by the year 2030, and that,
figuring 400 kg of grain for each person annually, the country
will need an annual grain output of 640 million tons. That means a
net increase of 150 million tons in next three decades.
</P>
<P>
The past has shown, both in China and in other parts of the
world, that agronomy can bring great changes in farm production,
and there will be better seed breeding, use of resources, farm
tools, and bio-technology by the year 2010. By the middle of next
century, China's farm production will be much more modernized, it
says.
</P>
<P>
Although China cut the acreage of land sown in grain crops by
10 million ha through scientific farming, the country's total
grain output rose from 300 million tons in 1978 to 490 million
tons last year as a result of agro-technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
