<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richer Rural Households In China Now Investing In Water Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Some of the richer families in
rural parts of China have begun to invest in water control
projects for development and to help the needy as well, because
they have enough thanks to the country's reforms.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhong Prefecture in Shanxi Province, in the north, is one of
these places. Its policies encourage farmers to put their money in
water conservation projects, so that whoever spends will benefit
from the project. The local government also provides subsidies for
large-scale, high-efficiency projects, and floating prices for
water for investors.
</P>
<P>
About 200 households in the prefecture have spent 32 million
yuan in all on eight water diversion projects and four water
saving and supply projects. These have helped the improvement of
200 ha of medium- and low-yield farmland and the development of
2,200 ha of irrigated farmland.
</P>
<P>
Yan Jiusan, of Pingyao County, spent 140,000 yuan on a well
to improve 10 ha of arid land, which he has turned into an
orchard. Yan also helps irrigate more than 70 ha of land for other
villagers.
</P>
<P>
Gui Gairun, of Shouyang County, has worked hard on 220 ha. of
hilly wasteland over the past decade, and put more than 100,000
yuan into planting 150 ha. of shelterbelt.
</P>
<P>
Next, rich families that were not involved in agriculture began
to follow suit. Cao Yishang, of Jiexiu city, who made his money in
the coke business, invested 900,000 yuan in shoreland along the
Fenhe River where he plans to spend 15 million yuan on a large
water storage project to ease the water shortage problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Joining Hands With HK in Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Petroleum Administration has been cooperating fruitfully with a
Hong Kong company in jointly exploring petroleum resources in
Junggar Basin since September of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The two companies have successfully sunk 540 oil wells this
year, which will be able to produce 625,000 tons of crude oil,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
In September 1996, Xinjiang Petroleum Administration signed a
contract with China (Hong Kong) Oil Co. Ltd. for establishing
Xinjiang-HK Petroleum Cooperative Development Company which will be
responsible for a joint exploration of two thick oil structures
situated on northwestern border of the Junggar Basin.
</P>
<P>
The new company, with a registered capital of over one billion
yuan, is the first share-holding company engaged in oil
development in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang Petroleum Administration set aside 480 million yuan on
the cooperative venture, while the Hong Kong partner pumped in 66
million U.S. dollars (about 548 million yuan).
</P>
<P>
According to a signed agreement, all the oil produced by the
joint venture will be purchased by Xinjiang Petroleum
Administration in line with existing market prices and the profits
will be divided by proportions.
</P>
<P>
Yang Ruiqi, a senior researcher with Xinjiang Petroleum
Research Institute, said the northwestern border of the Junggar
Basin is home to one billion thick oil resources, but currently,
the verified geological thick oil reserves in the region only
stands at 200 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The two thick oil structures Xinjiang and Hong Kong have been
cooperating on are rich in oil reserves which are not buried deep,
therefore cost for sinking wells will be comparatively low. The
joint venture has so far formed production capacity.
</P>
<P>
Thick oil exploration in Junggar Basin only has a history of
more than ten years, but a complete set of thick oil exploring
technology from geological research, oil exploring techniques and
ground treatment has been formed.
</P>
<P>
The application of high-pressure steam to the oil-bearing
strata has greatly enhanced thick oil output. Junggar Basin is
expected to produce 1.93 million tons of thick oil this year,
accounting for a quarter of China's total output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
