<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministers Sign Two Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
nine ASEAN nations today signed a Memorandum of Understanding
(MOU) concerning the set-up of the ASEAN Foundation with a view to
organizing and supporting activities to promote education,
training, health and culture.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ASEAN economic ministers also clinched a Protocol to
Implement the Initial Package of Commitments Under the ASEAN
Framework Agreement on Services.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremonies, which were witnessed by the ASEAN
leaders, were held at the end of the one-day second ASEAN informal
summit presided over by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
here today.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, the foundation will offer fellowships and
support exchanges of ASEAN youth and students, and promote
collaborative work among academics, professionals and scientists.
</P>
<P>
The foundation, which was agreed upon by ASEAN leaders at their
first informal summit held in Jakarta, Indonesia, in November last
year, would be located in Jakarta and managed by a board of
trustees, an executive director and an advisory council.
</P>
<P>
Under the Protocol, ASEAN countries committed to according
preferential treatment in market access for trade services
beginning March 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The initial package will cover tourism, maritime and air
transport, business services and telecommunications, and a second
phase of negotiations will start next year for a final package of
commitments to be completed by the end of next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
