<HEADLINE> Southern China's Private Sector Assists State Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Private businesses in the
capital of south China's Guangdong Province have been playing a
positive role in State-owned enterprise reforms.
</P>
<P>
They are co-operating mainly in purchasing companies and buying
shares, and are injecting some vitality into lack-luster
state-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
One privately-owned company rejuvenated the Guangzhou
Fireproofing Plant, which was on the verge of bankruptcy, by
buying it for 13 million yuan (1.57 million US dollars). Another
private firm purchased an air-conditioner plant for 95 million
yuan (11.45 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some private businesses support State-owned companies that are
short of funds by purchasing idle State-owned fixed assets. The
Jinxiang Industrial Co. bought a 600 sq.m. workshop from a
State-owned plant for three million yuan (361,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Buying shares has also been proven effective. The Huangpu Port
Development Co., which had a handling capacity of only 7,000
containers in 1996, expanded its operations when 40 million yuan
(4.8 million US dollars) of its shares were bought by a local
private firm.
</P>
<P>
The area of Huangpu Port has increased from 18,000 sq.m. to
100,000 sq.m. and the annual handling capacity has risen to 40,000
containers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Urbanites Learn How To Find Jobs From Rural Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese state statistics show
that 35.91 million farmers, equivalent to the number of workers
expected to be laid off in cities from 1991 to 2000, have found
jobs in cities, today's People's Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
Most people living in urban areas experience some inconvenience
when those rural laborers temporarily leave their posts in large
numbers, especially during the Spring Festival when they go back
home to reunite with their families.
</P>
<P>
These laborers have taken the jobs of city people, but the
truth is that most of those former farmers are doing the dirtiest
and most tiresome jobs that urbanites extremely dislike, such as
physical labor, selling vegetables, construction work, and street
food vending.
</P>
<P>
And, those 35 million workers earned a total of 197.3 billion
yuan, or nearly 24 billion US dollars, from that hard menial work,
according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
"The factory where I worked paid me only 300 yuan a month, but
I could knit sweaters during working hours," one person explained,
"but now, a 600-yuan job requires much harder work, and I feel
that it just isn't worth it."
</P>
<P>
Some big cities have restrictions on hiring rural laborers. But
the key to dealing with unemployed urbanites, the news story says,
lies in changing their attitudes.
</P>
<P>
Many laid-off workers in Shanghai have looked for work as
part-time domestic help or nurses, jobs that were formerly
regarded as suitable for rural laborers only, and, the news story
goes on to say, urban workers should learn from their rural
counterparts in looking for work.
</P>
<P>
"Some Beijing people are lazy, but they're willing to part with
their money, we can earn over 200 yuan a day by washing six range
hoods for them," say two farmer-workers from Sichuan, who describe
how they even collected scrap after arriving in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The 35 million rural laborers had to look for work in urban
environments they were completely unfamiliar with, and urban
residents must learn how to find a way out as the country
restructures its economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
