<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Peace Still Keynote in West Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- For west Africa, the most
important thing worth celebrating this year is the restoration of
peace in Liberia, a historical victory that people all over the
sub-region hope to bring an enabling environment for economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Then there came an event of similar importance but with
adverse effect.
</P>
<P>
It was the military coup in Sierra Leone which took place as
the Liberian peace process was approaching its end, and this coup
once again exposed the sub-region to chaos both politically and
economically.
</P>
<P>
West African countries, over the past seven years or more,
have been deeply upset by the bloody civil war in Liberia, which
not only destroyed the country, but also threw the entire
sub-region in its shadow.
</P>
<P>
Billions of U.S. Dollars and tens of thousands of troops under
the aegis of ECOMOG, the peace-keeping force of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), have been put into
Liberia by its peace-loving neighbors and their painstaking
efforts have finally borne the desired fruit.
</P>
<P>
With the assistance of ECOWAS and the international community
as a whole, and under the monitoring of ECOMOG, a successful
election in August this year produced the country's post-war
government led by President Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Peace returned at long last as a milestone in the history of
Liberia after seven years of nightmare, during which more than
150,000 people were killed and about 800,000 others fled to
neighboring countries for refuge.
</P>
<P>
However, it still seems early for both the leaders and the
people of west African countries to be jubilant over the
returning peace and normalcy in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Only eight weeks before Liberia's first post-war election,
rebellious soldiers in neighboring Sierra Leone launched a coup
and ousted the 14-month-old civilian government of President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The May 25 coup aroused condemnation from the international
community. The United Nations and ECOWAS have both imposed
sanctions against the country as a means to force the ruling
military junta to step down.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were accompanied by a series of negotiations
during which the junta finally agreed to hand over power to
President Kabbah in April next year.
</P>
<P>
However, as consensus has yet been reached on certain critical
issues for the hand-overr, observers doubted if the peace process
in Sierra Leone could proceed smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Sierra Leonean crisis, everyone is convinced that
owing to the collective efforts by ECOWAS member states, the
situation in west Africa as a whole is moving toward stability.
</P>
<P>
It is especially so when taking into consideration the
achievements in Liberia and the improvement in the relations
between Ghana and Burkina Faso which had been frozen for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
The protocol signed earlier this month between the government
of Niger and its opposition on the implementation of a peace
accord and the calmness at the Nigeria-Cameroun border also
contribute to the situation.
</P>
<P>
All this will help create an environment favorable for west
African countries to boost economic development.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, west African countries have never given
up their effort on economic development despite instability in
the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics provided by the ECOWAS secretariat,
economy in the sub-region started to grow in 1993, with the
growth rate moving up to 2.8 percent in 1994 and four percent in
1995, which was higher than the three-percent population growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the sub-region recorded an economic growth rate as
high as 4.3 percent, and similar achievement is expected this
year as a result of good weather conditions and the redoubled
efforts by various countries in restructuring the economy as well
as increasing foreign investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: Peace Still Keynote in West Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, as analysts pointed out, the real economic take-off
in west Africa as a whole depends, to a large extent, on the good
performance of ECOWAS, a 16-member sub-regional body set up 22
years ago with an ambition of economic integration through joint
efforts and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
To build a sub-regional bloc similar to the European Union,
ECOWAS members have adopted such impressive programs as
harmonization of national macro-economic policies, establishment
of a single monetary zone and trade liberalization scheme.
</P>
<P>
The programs also include regional infrastructural networks,
gas project, inter-connection of national electric grids,
regional environmental protection and food security.
</P>
<P>
Previous efforts in carrying out these community schemes have
led to significant achievements.
</P>
<P>
According to ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate,
customs regulations and formalities in the sub-region have been
harmonized so that customs services within the community could
use uniform codes and descriptions following the adoption of a
common nomenclature.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 16 members, 14 countries in west Africa have
computerized their systems to facilitate customs formalities,
which will give a boost to inter-community trade.
</P>
<P>
The 4,460-km trans-Sahelian highway linking Dakar, Senegal and
Ndjamena, Chad is 85 percent completed, while the trans-coastal
road between Lagos and Nouakchott is 87 percent accomplished.
</P>
<P>
Plans are underway to establish a coastal shipping line and
institutional reform is in progress to liberalize the use of
airspace of member states.
</P>
<P>
The west African gas pipeline project, which will supply
Nigeria's gas to Benin, Togo and Ghana, is to be put into
construction soon, while a master plan has been evolved
concerning the provision of hydro-electric power and the
inter-connection of electricity grids across the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
All these, however, are far from what should have been
achieved.
</P>
<P>
As ECOWAS chairman, Nigeria's head of state General Sani
Abacha once put it, "Much has not been done and has to be done
particularly when the ultimate objectives, such as the creation
of a common customs union by the year 2000 and that of an
economic and monetary union by 2005, are concerned."
</P>
<P>
It is therefore a logic development that west African leaders
who met last August at the Abuja summit adopted a package of
measures to promote sub-regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed to implement sound macro-economic policies
to consolidate their respective success in inflation control,
monetary discipline and improved adjustment programs.
</P>
<P>
The strong political will the leaders expressed to further
cooperate for prosperity in the region is encouraging. But to
many observers, they have to redouble their efforts to turn the
good will into reality.
</P>
<P>
What disturbs observers is the failure to launch the
long-awaited ECOWAS travellers check scheduled for earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
When governors from the Central Banks of ECOWAS member states
gathered in Dakar, Senegal last week to finalize the launching,
the Francophone countries said they would not participate in the
scheme until some members settled their arrears of debts through
the sub-regional clearing mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Although efforts are underway to bring these countries back to
the negotiation table, the incident served as a touchstone for
sub-regional leaders to demonstrate their determination and
sincerity in putting their commitment into practice, an analyst
here said.
</P>
<P>
In the same vein, what west Africa needs urgently is to ensure
peace and security which are indispensable for development.
</P>
<P>
As Kouyate noted, nothing enduring can be built in a climate
of violence and instability.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate's view was echoed at the just-concluded 42nd session
of the ECOWAS council of ministers.
</P>
<P>
The ministers meeting in the Nigerian capital of Abuja earlier
this week urged strict observation of the ECOWAS and the United
Nations sanctions against the military junta in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Worried by the stranded peace process in that country, the
ministers called for an early resolution of the crisis there so
as to restore peace to the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that some individual countries with good
environment can achieve faster growth and become the power houses
for sub-regional development.
</P>
<P>
But their role will be limited when elements of instability
still pose a threat to peace in the entire sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, when west African leaders decide to shift the focus
of their efforts to economic development, they have to keep in
mind that peace keeping is often necessary and they should always
be ready to make contribution in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
