<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second ASEAN Informal Summit Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The second ASEAN Informal
Summit opened here today with a view to seeking ways of addressing
the financial and economic problems now affecting the Southeast
Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the one-day meeting, the leaders of ASEAN nations
are expected to issue a statement on the current financial
problems and a document entitled "the ASEAN Vision 2020" which
offers a road map for ASEAN in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
In addition, two documents -- the Memorandum of Understanding
to establish the ASEAN Foundation and the Protocol to Implement
the Initial Package of Commitments Under ASEAN Framework Agreement
on Services will be signed by ASEAN foreign ministers and economic
ministers respectively in the presence of the leaders during the
summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit is being attended by all ASEAN leaders except
Indonesian President Soeharto who is absent due to health reasons.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
