<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Destruction of Tainted Food Hurts Sri Lankan Traders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's large scale
campaign to destroy contaminated food so as to contain a cholera
epidemic has affected small and medium scale food industrialists.
</P>
<P>
About 400 businessmen have suffered losses due to destruction
of their food stocks, sources in the Sri Lankan Foundation for the
Development of Small and Medium Scale Industries said today. The
organization represents more than 4,500 businessmen nation-wide.
</P>
<P>
The sources said those affected have urged Health Minister
Nimal Siripala de Silva to stop "the indiscriminative destruction
of food items."
</P>
<P>
Public health inspectors have destroyed ice cream, yogurt and
cordials produced by the businessmen to help curb the
wide-spreading cholera epidemic in the nation.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, eight deaths caused by cholera have been reported
and 273 patients hospitalized in Sri Lanka since the disease began
to spread in September.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, traders were told by health inspectors to
refrain from purchasing and marketing food items produced by small
scale industrialists.
</P>
<P>
The move has caused certain losses to those food producers or
owners, who complained they were unable to pay salaries or repay
bank loans, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They argued that it was unfair for the authorities to impose
food inspection regulations only against the small and medium
scale industry sector and destroy their food items
indiscriminately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
