<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Currency Assets Dip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign currency assets of
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) dipped by 485 million U.S. dollars
for the week ending December 5 though there was no "active"
intervention by the central bank in the foreign exchange markets,
local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The decline in foreign currency assets was less compared to the
previous week when it had dropped by 772 million dollars due to
active intervention by the RBI in the foreign exchange markets in
the country to check the sustained devaluation of the rupee.
</P>
<P>
During the week under review, the foreign exchange markets in
India were calmer as the RBI had announced a fresh set of measures
to suck rupee liquidity, raise dollar deposits of banks and
contain excessive speculation by dealers.
</P>
<P>
With the further fall in foreign currency assets, the foreign
exchange reserves of the RBI, which also include gold and special
drawing right reserves, fell by 627 million dollars to 27.487
billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
