<HEADLINE> Croatia, Yugoslavia to Open Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Croatia and Yugoslavia will
formally open seven border check points at midnight Sunday to
implement an agreement signed by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the border agreement, which went into effect Saturday,
the seven border check points opened earlier Saturday include Ilok
and Batina, the official newspaper of Croatia Viesnik reported.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the borders marked further improvement of the
relations between the two countries. Their highways and railroads
have already been opened this year.
</P>
<P>
The citizens of the two countries can cross border freely to
visit their relatives and friends and to go to work or school
after they get visas and border passes.
</P>
<P>
As of December 12, Croatia has released 8,000 entry-exit visas
and border passes to those Serbs working and studying in Croatia,
and the Yugoslav Embassy in Croatia also has granted 5,000 visas
to Croatian citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
