<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Unscathed Singapore Prepared for Worse (1)  by Zeng Hu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 15 (Xinhua) -- As the eventful 1997 is
drawing to a close, the latest episode of the currency turmoil,
which has hit several major economies in Southeast Asia since
July, is still unabated and Singapore is getting prepared for
stormy weather ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore economy has so far remained relatively unscathed
in the financial crisis that has played havoc with Asian
economies, which represented an important part of Asia's
miraculous economic growth.
</P>
<P>
However, observers here warn that if the crisis is allowed to
go on unsubdued, it would be a matter of time before Singapore too
is hit.
</P>
<P>
The mighty Singapore dollar, which had depreciated by about 12
percent against the U.S. dollar while other currencies in the
region had fallen by more than 20 to 40 percent as of last month,
was brought further down last Friday as Asian stock and currency
markets continued to be battered by the fallout from the financial
crisis in South Korea and the news that Indonesian President
Soeharto canceled his planned trip to Malaysia to attend an ASEAN
(Association of South East Asian Nations) informal summit because
of his health.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore dollar broke through the 1.65 level Friday,
hitting a 58-month low of 1.653 against the greenback and marking
a 15.6 percent decline from its July 1 level of 1.43 to the U.S.
dollar. Local media reports said that dealers were expecting the
Singapore currency to test the 1.70 level soon.
</P>
<P>
Despite its sound economic fundamentals and the fact that it
had been an exceptional example in the region that withstood the
storm in the foregoing months, it is obvious that Singapore, its
currency and its economic growth, are being dragged lower by the
mishaps in the other countries in the region and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
As demands for electronic products picked up in the U.S. and
European markets, Singapore had been doing quite well in the first
three quarters of the year, recovering from last year's slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Propelled by the resurgent electronics sector, the country's
gross domestic product (GDP) witnessed a remarkable 10.1 percent
growth in the third quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
This, again, testified to the economy's resilience and
officials from the Ministry for Trade and Industry expected the
momentum to continue into the current final quarter and cap the
full-year growth at around 7 percent, which was revised upwards
from the early projection of 6 to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to its well-regulated management of the financial
sector, one more reason why Singapore succeeded in shielding
itself from the worst effects of the regional crisis is the
diversity of its economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Unscathed Singapore Prepared for Worse (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Observers note that each major sector, be it financial services
or communications, has become an important engine in its own
right. Furthermore, while intra-Asia trade and investments have
increased, Singapore's final markets mainly remain the developed
countries in North America and Europe, which at present lie well
beyond the striking distance of the crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Ministry for Trade and Industry recognized that a
large part of Singapore's regional trade consists of intra-firm
movement of parts and components by multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here say that all this should not be taken to
mean that Singapore could jump out of the crisis all by itself and
soon.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, they point out once again that although
Singapore has been doing much better in many ways than its
hard-hit neighbors, it will have to be and is being affected by
the developments in countries around it and its economic growth
will pick up steam only after the neighbors are on their feet
again.
</P>
<P>
They say that now in Singapore, the manufacturing upswing has
masked a significant downturn in the services sector. Tourism is
expecting to see "near zero" growth in visitor arrivals this year,
and the retail sector is getting the bite.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, with mortgage rates on the rise, the property
sector will have to grapple with a continuing slide in home prices
and with its consequent negative "wealth effect," while
developers, banks and other property-related businesses are in for
a long haul.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Tony Tan said late last month
that Singapore could not escape being hit by the regional turmoil
over the next two years. The big question, he said, is whether the
region suffers a short, sharp downturn, or a prolonged period of
slow or no growth.
</P>
<P>
The key, he stressed, is whether the regional governments are
prepared to take the bitter medicine necessary to nurse their
economies back to good health.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the right prescription is followed, the
short-term pain will be considerable but a robust recovery will
follow. Otherwise, the alternative is a long malaise, which will
eventually cause more hardship in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Unscathed Singapore Prepared for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Whether there is a sharp slowdown or worse a prolonged period
of low or no growth, Singapore will not be totally unaffected.
Because our economic situation is fundamentally sound, we may not
suffer as much as the regional countries. However, as the
Singapore economy is closely linked through trade and investment
with the region, we must be prepared that the regional slowdown
will impact, hopefully not severely, our economic growth in 1998
and perhaps also in 1999," the deputy prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
When releasing the country's third quarter economic survey last
month, the Ministry for Trade and Industry said some moderation of
growth can be expected as regional growth slows down. The
ministry's preliminary 1998 GDP forecast is 5 to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, three weeks later, Minister for Trade and Industry Lee
Yock Suan said that the government would review its economic
growth forecast for next year of between 5 and 7 percent because
of the financial crisis that had hit the South Korean economy.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing currency and economic turmoil in the region was
bound to have some impact on Singapore, although it was still
difficult to say how big the impact would be, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The signs are that this year the economy is still doing well,
but next year we have to watch and see," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here note that as the crisis rages on with no sign of
coming to an end soon, several international investment houses
have cut down their 1998 forecast of Singapore's growth to around
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The recent developments have given rise to calls for Singapore
to get prepared for "a long spell of heavy weather." When asked if
the government would be embarking on any new policies as a result
of the recent crisis, Lee Yock Suan said the government Committee
on Singapore's Competitiveness, which he chairs, was still doing
its work and promised that the committee would have to "take stock
of the new situation".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Products Sold to Other Parts of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- While products from many parts
of China continue to pour into Tibet, the autonomous region is
also expanding the spread of its products to other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
A group of local products with ethnic characteristics like
"Hongjingtian Tonic Tea", "Lhasa Carpets", and "Lhasa Beer" are
moving into the markets in many parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Although many are still in the initial stage of making a name
in the central and eastern Chinese markets, sales are
increasing. "Nearly 70 percent of our products are sold in central
and eastern markets," says the director of the Lhasa Food Plant,
whose major product is tonic tea and which has sales centers in
Beijing, Xi'an, Shenzhen, Xiamen and Luoyang. The company also
plans to launch a nationwide advertising campaign before the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
Some Tibetan factories took part in a recent exhibition in
Shanghai and Tibetan businessmen are confident about entering the
central and eastern markets although the Tibetan economy is
backward.
</P>
<P>
"Many of the plateau products here are rare and they are very
competitive," says one Tibetan businessman.  
</P>
