<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiat Leadership Unaltered by Death of Agnelli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The death of Giovanni Alberto
Agnelli, the acknowledged heir to the Fiat auto empire, will not
change the accepted scenario for the group's leadership in the
near future, Fiat Honorary Chairman Gianni Agnelli said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Fiat-owned daily La Stampa, he said
his nephew Alberto Agnelli was never in line to take over at the
company helm when current Chairman Cesare Romiti retires in 1998
or 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Some time would have had to pass before he could have taken on
his full responsibilities," the honorary chairman said after
Alberto Agnelli, head of the Piaggio scooter-maker, died of cancer
at the age of 33 at home in Turin last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
His death changed the long term scenario, but had no immediate
effect on Italy's largest industrial group, said Agnelli, grandson
of Fiat's founder Giovanni Agnelli.
</P>
<P>
"It's a terrible drama for the family," said a Fiat spokesman.
"But it's a private one. It's not a drama for the company, which
is a multinational led by a group of top-rank managers."
</P>
<P>
Romiti's successor is unlikely to be another Agnelli family
member, because there is no candidate with the training or
inclination to take the helm.
</P>
<P>
It was said that top Fiat consultant Paolo Fresco and Managing
Director Paolo Cantarella may have the possibility to replace
Romiti.
</P>
<P>
Agnelli said this summer that he had a candidate in mind to
replace Romiti, but declined to say who it was.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Agnelli's death will put off indefinitely the moment
when an Agnelli returns to take the reins of Fiat, whose managing
leadership had only two outsiders since the auto company was
established. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
