<HEADLINE> Thailand's Rice Cereals See Export Potential: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's cereal products
made from rice flour have high potentials for export sale,
according to a study of the Thai Farmers Research Center available
today.
</P>
<P>
These products include rice crackers, instant noodles and
glutinous flour.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports of rice cereals expanded steadily in the
last ten years, rising from 84,000 tons in 1986 to 143,000 tons in
1996, with the total value increased from 930 million baht (37
million U.S. dollars) to 3.3 billion baht (78.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months this year, exports of the products
totaled 93,500 tons, earning 2.49 billion baht (59 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Asians living in the United States are the main buyers of Thai
instant noodles, while Japan is the largest importer of Thai rice
crackers, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The weakening baht has given an extra edge to exports of these
products, the study said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
