<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Confidence Down in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Japanese business confidence
worsened for both manufacturers and nonmanufacturers, reflecting the
country's prolonged economic slump, according to a key quarterly
survey report released by the Bank of Japan (BOJ) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in its Tankan report that the key diffusion
index measuring the sentiment of executives of major manufacturers
fell to minus 11 in the December survey from a positive 3 in the
September report.
</P>
<P>
The central bank had predicted in the September survey that the
index would drop in December, but remain in positive territory at 1.
</P>
<P>
The BOJ said in the latest survey that the index for major
nonmanufacturers fell to minus 20.
</P>
<P>
It said the index for small and medium-sized manufacturers fell to
minus 21 from minus 13 in September, and to minus 25 for their
nonmanufacturing counterparts from minus 18.
</P>
<P>
The indexes, which are watched closely to gauge Japan's business
climate, are derived by subtracting the percentage of companies that
think business conditions are unfavorable from the percentage that say
prospects are looking up.
</P>
<P>
Nonmanufacturers include the service, construction, real estate,
trading and telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead, the survey showed the confidence index for major
manufacturers is expected to fall further to minus 15 and that for
nomanufacturers to minus 22 by the time next report is released in
March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
