<HEADLINE> Thailand's Trade Edge Lost in Asian Currency Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda has admitted that the country is losing its
prospective trading edge as Asian currencies continue to plunge
against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
As the Korean won, Indonesian rupiah, Malaysian ringgit and
Japanese yen continue to drop against the dollar, Thailand's hopes
to gain a competitive edge in exports through the baht's slide
have been dashed, the Bangkok Post today quoted Tarrin as saying
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The regional economic crisis means that Thailand's markets in
Asia have seen a decline in buying power, reducing demand for Thai
products.
</P>
<P>
He said the region is now experiencing capital flight as global
investors head for safer havens in their home markets.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we have to help ourselves... we have to take action,
decisively and expeditiously."
</P>
<P>
He said the most critical task for the government now was to
deal with the problems of the financial sector, to enable the
system to serve as a foundation and efficient intermediary for the
rest of the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
