<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Regulations On Random Firing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Authorities in south China's
Guangdong Province recently publicized a new regulation
prohibiting the random firing of people by local businesses.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stipulates that business should not fire
employees who have worked for ten years and who are within five
years of retiring, or who have worked for 20 years and are over
45, if male, and 40, if female.
</P>
<P>
In addition, companies cannot dismiss worker delegates who
take part in contract negotiations with employers, or the spouses
of already fired workers, who worked in the same company.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises must get approvals from labor departments above
prefectural levels if the firing is imperative, the regulation
says.
</P>
<P>
Labor departments have urged employers to provide vocational
training for those people who have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also says that local businesses should give
preference to their former employees when deciding to hire workers
again within six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
