<HEADLINE> Developing International Service Trade In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's developmental
priority for the next century centers on the international service
trade, according to a Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Department official.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Xiaoming, director of the department, says that China's
largest port and manufacturing center has an edge in exports, but
that increasing labor and raw material costs, combined with a
cargo shortage, have resulted in a drop in some industrial exports.
</P>
<P>
So, Shanghai plans to use this as an opportunity for industrial
restructuring to place greater emphasis on the service sector,
in design, investment, circulation of goods, warehousing and
advertising.
</P>
<P>
The city has drawn up a three-year plan, whereby service trade
earnings, which accounted for 42 percent of Shanghai's GDP last
year, will reach eight billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000,
equivalent to 21 percent of the city's cargo trade.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will also adopt some international practices and form
large enterprise groups to lift the ratio of the service sector to
the GDP to 60 percent of the city's total by 2010.  
</P>
</TEXT>
