easily won the 15-kilometer cross country leg Sunday to claim his
first victory in four events of Nordic combined World Cup this
season.
</P>
<P>
The victory enabled Stecher to reclaim the FIS World Cup's
leader's bib from Hannu Manninen of Finland.
</P>
<P>
Manninen suffered visibly during the longer second race and
dropped back to 24th place, four minutes, 34.5 seconds behind the
winner.
</P>
<P>
After launching a pair of spectacular jumps on the K112 big
hill Saturday, Stecher carried a 50-second advantage over teammate
David Kreiner entering Sunday's race. Stecher's winning time of
37:52.5 combined with his jump points of 248.6 for a decisive
victory.
</P>
<P>
Second place went to Norway's Bjarte Engen Vik, who had a
cross country time of 37:06.2, but couldn't make up a 1:26 start
handicap and finished 39.7 seconds off the pace. Third went to
American Todd Lodwick, who finished 46.8 seconds back on his
hometown hill.
</P>
<P>
Reigning World Cup champion Kenji Ogiwara of Japan placed
eighth in Sunday's combined results, 2:28 behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
Stecher has a 10-point lead over Vik in the overall standings,
485 to 475. Manninen is third with 397. 
