<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Provinces Enhances Farmland Productivity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Three provinces in northeast
China, the country's major commercial grain-producing center, have
been pursuing high grain yields to increase output.
</P>
<P>
During the last three years Liaoning, Jilin and Heilongjiang
provinces improved 2.45 million hectares of mid- and low-yield
land and reclaimed 407,000 hectares of wasteland, which added 14
million tons to their total grain output.
</P>
<P>
The three provinces have a large potential for increasing the
per-unit grain yield. Official figures show that the region has 16
million hectares of arable land, 9 million hectares of which
proved to have a yield of less than 2.25 tons each. The region
also has vast tracts of wasteland, which has been estimated at 2
million hectares.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Province for example, has 80 percent of its
farmland in low-productive farming. During the last 10 years, work
has been finished on 520 million cubic meters of earth reclamation
and 1.4 million hectares of farmland has been transformed. The
effort has added 9.975 million tons of grain, or 45.9 percent of
total grain output in the corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
Also taken into account is investment in improving and
upgrading farmland. In recent trade talks held in Harbin, capital
city of the province, 200 land-promotion projects were open for
investment.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, local sources reported that contracts signed with
Shenzhen and Hong Kong investors are expected to bring 300 million
yuan (36 million US dollars) for transforming 41,300 hectares of
wasteland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Finds Emergency Requests for Food, Shelter up in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Despite a surging economy
and low unemployment, demand for emergency food and shelter
continued to grow this year, according to a survey by U.S.
Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 29 cities, to be made public Monday, contains
good and bad news on how the nation's poor are coping.
</P>
<P>
The good news is that requests for emergency housing are up
just 3 percent -- the smallest increase in the survey's 13-year
history.
</P>
<P>
On the down side, requests for emergency food rose an average
of 16 percent, the largest increase since 1992, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
Among the reasons, officials said, are low wages and high
housing costs. Nearly all the cities expected demand for food and
shelter to rise next year.
</P>
<P>
The survey, based on self-reporting by the cities, found:
</P>
<P>
-- Emergency food assistance requests increased in 24 of the 29
cities surveyed.
</P>
<P>
-- About one-fifth of emergency food help demands is estimated
to have gone unfulfilled. Only two cities reported that no food
assistance request went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
-- And, seventeen of the cities saw shelter requests rise,
while the number of emergency shelter beds among all the cities
decreased an average of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Officials of one city said the housing situation improved.
More common, however, are tales of reduced bed spaces and tougher
eligibility requirements.
</P>
<P>
Of the homeless population, about 47 percent are single men, 36
percent families with children, 14 percent single women and 4
percent minors, the survey found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
