<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Leftist Rebels Declare Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine leftist rebel
group, the New People's Army (NPA), has declared a 16-day
ceasefire starting on December 22 in keeping with the spirit of
the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of the Philippines and its armed wing, the
NPA, said in a communique that the ceasefire was issued on
humanitarian grounds and as an act of goodwill.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire was issued apparently in response to an earlier
declaration of a 30-day ceasefire during the Christmas season
against the rebels by President Fidel Ramos, local press reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The unilateral ceasefire declared by Ramos took effect from
December 6, 1997 to January 4, 1998. But Ramos earlier said it
would not cover normal law enforcement activities by the military.
</P>
<P>
The government's ceasefire provided a conducive climate for the
resumption of peace negotiations between the government and the
NPA's political wing National Democratic Front (NDF) in the
Netherlands, where rebel leaders live.
</P>
<P>
A series of rebel attacks, including the abductions of a police
chief and an army sergeant in October in the southern Philippines,
prompted the government to suspend talks that have been proceeding
sporadically since 1992 in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
After the NPA freed the captives on December 5, the government
announced it would resume the talks in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party has fought the government for more than
three decades and still has a presence in many hinterland areas,
including some rural villages around metropolitan Manila.
</P>
<P>
Military statistics estimated that from a high of 25,600 NPA
fighters in 1986, the number of the NPA guerrillas has gone down
to 5,000 as of November 30 this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
