<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preferential Policies Help Job Search In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The provincial labor
department in central-south China's Hunan Province recently worked
out preferential policies to help accelerate the re-employment of
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises that hire unemployed workers and sign contracts of
more than a year with them are entitled to receive unemployment
compensation that would have been given to the workers by
insurance companies, in one lump sum.
</P>
<P>
With labor and tax department approval, small and medium-sized
enterprises that hire a certain number of unemployed workers can
have their taxes reduced.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers are also being encouraged to make a living on
their own, and those who do so voluntarily can get
compensation. Self-employed workers can also continue their
old-age pension, provided they continue to pay insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
According to reliable sources, the province has developed a
series of preferential policies since 1994, which have helped
re-employ approximately 80,000 workers, accounting for 51 percent
of the province's unemployed people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
