<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Services Prevail in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- In Shanghai's luxury shopping
malls, cosmetologists improve women's looks, sales girls
color customers' hair -- all free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The city's residents are getting used to the free services
provided by various businesses as a means of promotion.
</P>
<P>
"I often receive gift packs of shampoo and washing powder,"
said Zhang Lihong, who lives in a residential compound in the
Yangpu District, claiming that she has not bought shampoo for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Telephone Directory Company gave its yellow pages
free to businesses in 1994. This year's yellow pages have entered
into almost all urban family homes.
</P>
<P>
Ticket-free shows are not unusual. The large-scale square
concerts near the Bund especially get nationwide fame.
</P>
<P>
However, free service is not always welcome. Some customers are
uncomfortable with the touting for business.
</P>
<P>
"The free service is just for sales promotion," said Xu Bo. "I
would feel like owing them if I enjoyed the service but never
bought their products," said Bo, from neighboring Hangzhou City
who went shopping recently in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Hygiene is another problem. Some sales people even try a single
lipstick on 20 to 30 customers.
</P>
<P>
Most urbanites said that they favored the free service for
customers'' convenience, but not merely for profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution Menaces Health of Future Generations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are
cautioning that environmental pollution could pose serious threats
to future generations because of its harmful effects on genes.
</P>
<P>
Lin Xiuwu, a professor at Changchun-based Dr. Norman Bethune
Medical University (NBMU) and a 73-year-old specialist in the
field of heavy metal pollution, said that parents exposed to a
modicum of heavy metals for a long time increase the possibility
that their infants will suffer malformation or physical defect.
</P>
<P>
Lin's research shows that heavy metals could damage cell
membranes. It can trigger a series of disturbances inside the
cell, including alterations of micro structure of the cell and of
its enzyme. Finally, the damage affects DNA.
</P>
<P>
Scientists further found that heavy metals also produces huge
effects on the genital system of males. They can cause a reduction
in quantity of sperm as well as deforming sperm through their
effects on the changes of genetic substances.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, researchers added, fetuses are so fragile that they
are easily affected by heavy metals inside their mothers.
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhiwei, a 32-year-old professor of the NBMU, said that the
environment on Earth is increasingly deteriorated. More and more
chemical wastes -- especially heavy metals such as mercury,
amalgam, lead inside gasoline -- are being dumped into the human
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sun suggested that people take more food containing selenium or
sulphides to reduce the heavy metals' damage to the human body,
noting that garlic can help humans resist pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
