<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-14 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PM: Turkey to Halt Political Dialogue with EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz announced here today that the Turkish government will
halt its political dialogue with the European Union (EU) from
now on.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz made the remark at a press conference following a
cabinet meeting called today to study Turkey's policy toward the
EU, local TV reports said.
</P>
<P>
"The EU will never be addressed in any political negotiations,
but our bilateral relations with the EU states will continue,"
Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that Turkey will not participate in the
European conference scheduled for March in Britain although the
EU leaders attending the just-concluded Luxembourg summit had sent
an invitation to Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The EU summit meeting, which ended Saturday afternoon,
decided to exclude Turkey from the present EU enlargement process
on grounds that Turkey did not meet the standards of the
European bloc.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, however, said that the EU summit did not evaluate
Turkey's application issue in the same framework as other
candidate countries.
</P>
<P>
Biased, prejudiced and exaggerated assessments have been made
regarding Turkey's domestic issues and foreign policy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been sparing no effort for full EU membership but
so far no substantial progress has been made due to its
differences with the European body.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders held that Turkey has a long way to go in
improving its human rights record, resolving its disputes with
neighboring Greece as well as settling the Kurdish issue.
</P>
<P>
On EU's criticism of Turkey's policy towards Cyprus, Yilmaz
said that Turkey will not change its consistent position on the
Cyprus issue despite international pressure.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Ankara will speed up its integration
cooperation with the Turkish Cypriots on the Cyprus island if the
EU starts accessions negotiations with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry also issued a written statement
late today to protest the EU decision regarding Turkey's
membership bid, describing it as "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
British Ambassador to Ankara David Logan reportedly delivered a
message from British Prime Minister Tony Blair to Yilmaz, whose
content was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that Blair is apparently trying to
persuade Turkey to participate in the European Conference to
be held in Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971215.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-14 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots: EU's Decision to Kill Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Cypriots today
warned that the decision of the European Union (EU) to start
accession talks with Cyprus will kill the peace process, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Turkish Cypriots said EU's decision
will destroy the international efforts for the reunification of
the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Despite firm opposition of Turkey and the Turkish Cypriots, the
EU summit Saturday decided to start accession talks with Cyprus
next March.
</P>
<P>
The EU has only helped destroy the established framework for a
settlement of the Cyprus problem, which has emerged through the
process of intercommunal negotiations, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the Turkish Cypriots will take whatever steps
necessary in all fields, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into a southern Greek Cypriot community and
a northern Turkish Cypriot community in 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after an abortive pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been making efforts to seek a
solution to the protracted problem, but no tangible results have
been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
